commit_message:
[install] [suse] install missing dependency pyOpenSSL

This solves the following issue when trying to start Keystone:

---snip---
DistributionNotFound: The 'pyOpenSSL' distribution was not found and is
required by pysaml2
---snap---

Change-Id: I2948fe81115e5ec5ea1bf1f0d871a6808a4dbb97
Implements: blueprint installguide-liberty

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-13 18:23:40.000000000', 'message': 'Do not copy sources

We do not need to copy source files anymore with current
openstackdocstheme, unset html_show_sourcelink and html_copy_source
links. Report a bug works without these as well.

This reduces the amount of files we build and publish (for Install Guide
from 42 MB to 39 MB), and thus speeds up building (from 44 to 41s for
Install Guide) slightly.

commit_message:
Do not copy sources

We do not need to copy source files anymore with current
openstackdocstheme, unset html_show_sourcelink and html_copy_source
links. Report a bug works without these as well.

This reduces the amount of files we build and publish (for Install Guide
from 42 MB to 39 MB), and thus speeds up building (from 44 to 41s for
Install Guide) slightly.

Change-Id: Id3bc5ea168ed764f67d7a19fac8ad546f2f8eff8

commit_message:
Raise exception if policy doesn't exist

Currently, during rule list/show, if the specified policy
doesn't exist, it silently comes out, with no results.
From this behaviour we couldn't tell if policy doesn't
exist or there are no rules specified for the policy.

This commit raises policy exception if policy doesn't exist.

Change-Id: I43d32ab9b472b9df448bc8cf0072489753c36269

commit_message:
Tweaks to #nosec (+ ignore flag, - dead constant)

Adds a flag '--ignore-nosec' to address the situation where a user is
auditing a code base and wants to see all identified issues, not just
those that haven't been nosec'd.

Also removes SKIP_FLAGS from core/constants.py, as that is no longer
used within the Bandit code base.

Change-Id: I1cef004660ff4abedb7128844cc0f26b9fdcda42
Closes-Bug: #1499467

One question;  I believe for unofficial openstack projects the precedence is just to use the project name (e.g. #storlets) as the channel name, as opposed to say #openstack-storlets. Do let me know if that's not the case though, I can change that.

Thanks !"}, {'account_id': 8330, 'date': '2015-10-13 17:45:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 16237, 'date': '2015-10-13 17:47:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-13 19:17:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

One question; I believe for unofficial openstack projects the precedence is just to use the project name (e.g. #storlets) as the channel name, as opposed to say #openstack-storlets. Do let me know if that's not the case though, I can change that.

jeblair has an agreement with freenode admins to have permissions on the #openstack- prefixed channels, regardless of whether the project is named in the governance repo or not. Best to go with #openstack-<project> channel names."}, {'account_id': 17156, 'date': '2015-10-13 21:02:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

"

to see the commit history for these files refer to the above Change-Ids
in the tempest repository.

Partially implements blueprint migrate-service-clients-to-tempest-lib

[{'account_id': 6899, 'date': '2015-08-06 11:31:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 6899, 'date': '2015-08-06 11:32:13.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 6899, 'date': '2015-08-06 11:37:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 6577, 'date': '2015-08-06 11:39:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

couple questions:

- if we use our integration test, should we still install tempest ? or we use tempest for something else?

- I thought, that smoke tests create some stacks/resources and then (after upgrade) we try to operate them. Is it right? if yes, how we can do the same with current integrations tests (they clean all resources after testing)'}, {'account_id': 6899, 'date': '2015-08-06 12:03:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Sure skraynev. 

I think we could still use tempest.api.orchestration.* tests if we want. Apart from that, we really don't need tempest at the moment.

Smoke tests are only used for checking the sanity of the service before and after the upgrade. It doesn't do any specific verification of resources before/after the upgrade. So, because we were running smoke tests of other services which seemed unnecessary, I'm making Grenade only run heat_integrationtests, and specifically the quicker functional tests.

Upgrade tests themselves are all manual however. We'd have to manually write them. I've been otherwise wondering though if we could leverage existing heat_integrationtests like you suggest to run actual upgrade tests too in a hybrid manner. One idea is to just execute create_stack part of all heat_integrationtests in the pre-upgrade phase and then run the update_stack/delete_stack parts of the respective tests in the post-upgrade phase. That way, we'd act on the existing stacks from pre-release and run operations over them after upgrade to simulate an experience close to what the user has after upgrade. Disclaimer: Haven't thought this through ;)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-06 12:21:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

Thx for answer. 
About running tempest tests - will be better to ask other guys about their opinions, because I personally don't see real benefit of it (I'd prefer to remove tempest). It's also related with migrating most part of functional tests to our  Heat repository.

What's about running create part on one release and deleted on second - I don't think that it make sense. IMO, functional tests should check full functionality for each particular release.

The only one solution which I see here - using another manual tests (as you mentioned), but it probably should be  different tests (not totally similar on integration tests)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-07 05:34:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Grenade: Run select heat_integrationtests instead of tempest smoke

Only a few tests are run because these tests only verify the
sanity of the build rather than doing the upgrade tests itself. 

Closes-Bug: #1482152
partial blueprint upgrade-tests

Change-Id: I8fed19bd25cc3a62c03c35afafe2b662551dbd4e

to announce python 3.4 support for Heat.

commit_message:
Make services_client use **kwargs

As we discussed on
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-July/068864.html
All http POST/PUT methods need to contain **kwargs as their arguments.
This patch makes services_client use **kwargs.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: Ib5617c3957cf60b2c1f11b78b7c3a136adf7ef9d

commit_message:
Fix issue with su and bad kernels

Long story short, some kernels before 3.15 had an issue with using su
in a container when the network namespace was --net=host. The gate
has a 3.10 and a 3.13 kernel and has a problem with this. This changes
everything to use sudo

backport: liberty
Partially-Implements: blueprint functional-testing-gate
Change-Id: I4d79ccaa1cddffcc8393f64e7e1be2538efe33e5
(cherry picked from commit 5f200e044648efe64f297d186432839762f91395)

commit_message:
Bump ansible to 1.9.2

Ansible 1.9.2 contains the fix needed for docker-py >1.2.0

This is needed for some gate reasons, but it is also a good version
bump because it fixes a few issues with delegate_to.

Change-Id: Iafbabb3b0232620849d0548c5cd9d8d316c2b0f3
backport: liberty
Partially-Implements: blueprint functional-testing-gate
(cherry picked from commit c5be228be843222e9c9f2be36b92659ada3e25a8)

commit_message:
Add neutron plugin modules for Config Reference autogen

  Item 1 in #1503967)
    Add extra_repos/neutron-master for many plugins
    Add extra_repos/neutron-master-stackforge for stackforge plugins
      also edit autohelp-wrapper to handle stackforge url

  Item 3 in #1503967)
    Add object name re-mapping for
     networking-midonet
     networking-hyperv
     networking-bigswitch
     networking-edge-vpn
     networking-zvm
   on autohelp-wrapper

Change-Id: Ib247fed088446c79b7d9e6a9e1adbbc931108a3b
Partial-Bug: #1503967

commit_message:
Do not publish doctrees

Currently we published the cached sphinx build data (13 MB for
Install Guides) to docs.openstack.org. This is not needed at all. Invoke
build_sphinx in such a way that .dirtrees is not copied over.

Change-Id: Id96e75f2bbdc96b60aed9d9915bdd20f8eae6892
Depends-On: I541e0259b896afb5d92d4d23153a7d0a27a419e6

commit_message:
Add owner properties for profile object

This patch adds owner related properties for profile object, including
user, project and domain. These properties will be used to control
access privilege of profile objects.

Change-Id: I669fc151162bd8d6c0921eeee2616cb1f19a570e

Enable cinder-manage to remove services

This patch outlines how to use cinder-manage to
remove old services from the database.

Closes-Bug: #1485075

in place of su. There is no need to install newer kernel on Ubuntu.

Change-Id: I06eaa0bb0980f0698202724f523ab08cb344418e
'}, {'created': '2015-10-14 05:10:04.000000000', 'message': 'Cleanup outdated documentation

Kolla implements a workaround for the referenced docker issue. There is
no need to document it, however still recommend installing a recent
kernel for better compatibility.

Change-Id: I06eaa0bb0980f0698202724f523ab08cb344418e
'}]
commit_message:
Cleanup outdated documentation

Kolla implements a workaround for the referenced docker issue. There is
no need to document it, however still recommend installing a recent
kernel for better compatibility.

Change-Id: I06eaa0bb0980f0698202724f523ab08cb344418e

commit_message:
Abort disconnect if invalid udid

The vSCSI physical volume may hit an issue if there is an hdisk without
a UDID.  The connect flow handles this and will not map.  Which then
causes a revert.  However, during the revert the code tries to remove
the hdisk.  This causes a significant issue.

This change set detects this path by adding a flag to check if udid is
None.  If so, it presents a warning message to the operator.  It then
allows the revert flow to continue properly.

Change-Id: If7af35c7e7b68f9a5cf5496fdfded482b45064e0
Closes-Bug: 1505388

commit_message:
Fix support of dev use case with no auth

If --os-auth-url is not provided, then assume auth is not enabled. However,
if --os-password or --os-auth-token is provided, then use default auth URL
if it is not provided.

Change-Id: Iaba14949e1b507f440b1609eb2d58eb6b6399f1d
Closes-Bug: #1503915
(cherry picked from commit e9b8e75b725e09dab3706dae96038fddcbf1f88e)

commit_message:
Fix issue when stop/wait order is not respected

If stop/wait order is not respected, the following occurs:
* wait take the sever lock, and wait executor to finish
* then stop is called, try to get the lock to stop the executor
  but it can't because wait is waiting with the lock acquired

This change fixes that, and also removes the restriction
to call stop before wait. The lock and the _running flag
ensure that everything is called with the good order.

Change-Id: I9317928fd92c90cac9723dd6772348fbdbce33cf

commit_message:
Don't allow queries with 'IN' predicate with an empty sequence

While SQLAlchemy-based storage tests are run there is invoked an
SAWarning: `The IN-predicate on "image_locations.id" with an empty
sequence`. Fix the issue by making sure that the locations are not
empty.

Co-Authored-By: Alexei Kornienko <akornienko@mirantis.com>
Co-Authored-By: Kamil Rykowski <kamil.rykowski@intel.com>

Change-Id: Iad800a25f0a5ae3538dfc0821977b7086e080097

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-12 14:48:09.000000000', 'message': 'Fix test_misc for WebOb 1.5

WebOb 1.5 was released at 2015-10-11. With this new version,
webob.exc.WSGIHTTPException() constructor now fails with a KeyError
when the HTTP status code is 0.

test_exceptions_raise() of test_misc tries to instanciate all
exceptions of cinder.exception. The problem is that
ConvertedException uses a default HTTP status code of 0.

Modify the default HTTP status code of ConvertedException to 400 to
fix the unit test. The bug is only in the test,
cinder/api/openstack/wsgi.py copies an existing HTTP code:

    Fault(exception.ConvertedException(code=ex_value.code,  ...)

Closes-Bug: #1505153
Change-Id: I1aec8038774828d48da4b0e831b390e33243809a
(cherry picked from commit 867fccf833ffc597aa986cb6ff1b3b5c1101b9ba)

commit_message:
Squashed commit of WebOb 1.5 and oslo.db fixes

Add testresources and testscenarios used by oslo.db fixture

If we use oslo.db fixtures, we'll need these 2 packages or
the next version of oslo.db release will break us.

Closes-Bug: #1503501
Change-Id: I8facdaf69c79b1b1ae4f9f64e9856e12f14440ed
(cherry picked from commit ec40c3b6ddbfa4912ca6e612558efaef6043f3ae)

Fix test_misc for WebOb 1.5

WebOb 1.5 was released at 2015-10-11. With this new version,
webob.exc.WSGIHTTPException() constructor now fails with a KeyError
when the HTTP status code is 0.

test_exceptions_raise() of test_misc tries to instanciate all
exceptions of cinder.exception. The problem is that
ConvertedException uses a default HTTP status code of 0.

Modify the default HTTP status code of ConvertedException to 400 to
fix the unit test. The bug is only in the test,
cinder/api/openstack/wsgi.py copies an existing HTTP code:

    Fault(exception.ConvertedException(code=ex_value.code,  ...)

Closes-Bug: #1505153
Change-Id: I1aec8038774828d48da4b0e831b390e33243809a
(cherry picked from commit 867fccf833ffc597aa986cb6ff1b3b5c1101b9ba)

commit_message:
Fix order of arguments in assertEqual

assertEqual expects that the arguments provided to it should be
(expected, observed).If a particluar order is kept as a convention,
then it helps to provide a cleaner message to the developer if Unit Tests
fail. There are several Unit Test files where the arguments for assertEqual
have been swapped. This commit fixes the issue in lbaas.

Change-Id: I890deda05a26c9f84d7e2884970d051faa30830c
Partial-Bug: #1259292
Related-Bug: #1259292

commit_message:
Added LC_ALL to openrc

This commit adds the LC_ALL export to the openrc file to ensure that
the openstack clients and system work with different preset local
settings.

Change-Id: I9f62b9b3db50b70ebdddc724215ebd3b0a138e42
Closes-Bug: #1408935
(cherry picked from commit 456d5f2ee2cac30092fab28af3c53e57d22bd8a6)

commit_message:
Fix support of dev use case with no auth

If --os-auth-url is not provided, then assume auth is not enabled. However,
if --os-password or --os-auth-token is provided, then use default auth URL
if it is not provided.

Change-Id: Iaba14949e1b507f440b1609eb2d58eb6b6399f1d
Closes-Bug: #1503915

commit_message:
Fix order of arguments in assertEqual

Some tests used incorrect order assertEqual(observed, expected).
The correct order expected by testtools is
assertEqual(expected, observed).

Change-Id: I72e1d8a6b52fa6dbb85b57438aef92ad13735880
Partial-Bug: #1259292
(cherry picked from commit c10f06e2e84644c800a00c1a7ccf456f3ded6f08)

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Move FakeOneViewDriver to the fake.py module

All Fake drivers in tree lives under the fake.py module, this patch is
moving the FakeOneViewDriver to that module as well so we keep things
consistent and organized.

Change-Id: Ie3ecbf87037b353950acd6dd78503cad2e8a0221

commit_message:
Add device identifier to replication device

One thing that may be needed by some back ends
that are implementing replication is some sort
of back end device identifier.

For managed back ends this shouldn't be an issue
but for unmanaged, it's handy to have some sort
of identifier string.

This patch just adds that to the response examples
in the volume.manager code as well as adds an update
to the dev docs to point it out.

Change-Id: Ic113d905e65c756439425b03035179e65ce0b39e

commit_message:
Add a debugging userrc after keystone is up

As a follow-on to the issues raised by
I069f46f95656655ae7ba8f3dd929f47eae594b68, rather than a re-write of
create_userrc.sh logic, create a temporary userrc that can be helpful
for debugging until we have the whole system bootstrapped

Change-Id: I3325acffd259cf7f6f4a153c88037cfe8405ca50

commit_message:
[cli-reference] fix current version of python-mistralclient

'mistral --version' is broken in the release version of
python-mistralclient and will be fixed with
Iaa006fedb4ffacbadbaf3b04923eee868b83ad0b in a newer version. The
correct current version is 1.1.0.

Change-Id: Iff9bffbef531d80d2153100568dad3f9e45b6162

commit_message:
Add novnc console support

This change adds in support for the novnc console type in Nova.

* The change adds in a few new variables to the defaults which allow
  for the novnc console to be configued.
* A port entry was added to haproxy to support the console type.
* noVNC is being installed from source in the nova_console container.
  The git repo has been added to the openstack_other.yml repo-package file
  which allows for the repo to be cloned into the repo containers and then
  distributed out where needed from within the environment.

This cherry-pick was modified to remove the "vnc" section because that
configuration option within nova was not backported to kilo in upstream
nova.

Closes-Bug: 1428833

Change-Id: I221557aad77bf266b4e2fae23007ffa210aa1f75
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>
(cherry picked from commit 0681e25a5269e0b602207f10f72d0278769e85c8)
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Add 'deactivated' status to image schema.

New 'deactivated' status was introduced in Kilo release,
but it doesn't listed in available image statuses in the schema.

It leads to issues  on the client side, when it can't validate
the image with this status against the schema and returns the error.

Change-Id: I5ec264614ae7ecf54b846ad0600442a18c61d24c
Closes-bug: #1505218
Related-bug: #1505134

commit_message:
Add icmpv6 to list of valid values for protocol

This patch adds icmpv6 to expected values for protocol while
creating security group rule.

Change-Id: Ic5bd7b8bed14757c3de1c516aa521b8a7eb7fbaa
Closes-Bug: #1505786

commit_message:
Fix some bugs in 'dashboard_create_networks.rst'

"Create a network" form miss one item: "Admin State", and
the 'Subnet Detail' tab should be 'Subnet Details' tab.

Change-Id: I2868585a045d14ce7adf680dfd78a15add295936
Closes-bug: #1504453

[{'created': '2015-10-13 16:15:33.000000000', 'message': '[install] Liberty updates for heat

Update heat configuration for Liberty. Includes moving
stack creation to the launch instance section. Also
addresses some consistency issues, mostly from the RST
conversion.

Changes and testing specific to distribution packages
primarily involve Ubuntu. Other distributions may require
additional patches.

Change-Id: Ib1ba4987eabe15a2100a58d1448507c203fc25f3
Implements: blueprint installguide-liberty
'}]
commit_message:
[install] Liberty updates for heat

Update heat configuration for Liberty. Includes moving
stack creation to the launch instance section. Also
addresses some consistency issues, mostly from the RST
conversion.

Changes and testing specific to distribution packages
primarily involve Ubuntu. Other distributions may require
additional patches.

Change-Id: Ib1ba4987eabe15a2100a58d1448507c203fc25f3
Implements: blueprint installguide-liberty

[{'created': '2015-08-28 10:32:02.000000000', 'message': 'py3: Add json attribute to HTTP response objects

Add a json attribute to CreatedResponse and JSONResponse of
openstack_dashboard.api.rest.utils. Use this attribute in REST tests.

This change makes code more readable, but it was written to port
openstack_dashboard to Python 3. On Python 3, the hash function is now
randomized by default, so dictionary items are serialized in a random
order by JSON.

Partial-Implements: blueprint porting-python3
Change-Id: I8503ee530d4122b2ce733d02023454796934c8e6

commit_message:
py3: Add json attribute to HTTP response objects

Add a json attribute to CreatedResponse and JSONResponse of
openstack_dashboard.api.rest.utils.

This patch changes unit tests: they now compare deserialized JSON
data instead of comparing the serialized JSON data which depends on
the exact hash function

This change makes the code more readable, but it was written to port
openstack_dashboard to Python 3. On Python 3, the hash function is
now randomized by default, so dictionary items are serialized in a
random order by JSON. Moreover, the hash function is different on
Python 2 and Python 3, so setting PYTHONHASHSEED=0 in tox.ini is not
enough to have a reliable JSON serialized ouput in all cases.

Fix also NaNJSONEncoder: On Python 3, don't try to decode bytes from
the encoder encoding, since the JSON encoder has no more encoding on
Python 3: it produces an Unicode string.

Partial-Implements: blueprint porting-python3
Change-Id: I8503ee530d4122b2ce733d02023454796934c8e6
Co-Authored-By: Richard Jones <r1chardj0n3s@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Replace filter() with list-comprehension

Python 3, filter() returns an iterator, not a list.

commit_message:
Port remaining Horizon tests for Python 3

* XSS check: don't check the exact HTML output because the attributes
  of the <a> tag are rendered on a different order depending on the
  hash function. On Python 3, the hash function is now randomized.
* Replace table.columns.values() with list(table.columns.values())
  to get a list on Python 3.
* WorkflowsTests: cast the HTTP response to bytes(), not to str().
  On Python 2, bytes is str so the test pass on Python 2 and Python 3.
* tox.ini: run all Horizon tests on Python 3 (but keep the whitelist
  for the openstack dashboard)

Partial-Implements: blueprint porting-python3
Change-Id: I19c5710fe53c6cdd3814a1615cef7b27339c444c

commit_message:
Do not publish doctrees

Currently we published the cached sphinx build data (13 MB for Install
Guides) to docs.openstack.org. This is not needed at all. Invoke
build_sphinx in such a way that .doctrees is not copied over.

Change-Id: I541e0259b896afb5d92d4d23153a7d0a27a419e6

commit_message:
Update Cinder Configuration for Liberty

This patch includes the following updates based on the updated source in
Cinder's Liberty release:
 - api-paste.ini (no changes)
 - policy.json
 - rootwrap.d/volume.filters

DocImpact
UpgradeImpact
Implements: blueprint liberty-release

Version discovery was found to break deployments using proxies, so it was
reverted. This was introduced in python-cinderclient 1.2.0, persisted in
1.2.1 and 1.2.2, and reverted in 1.3.0 . The 1.2.? versions make note of this
in the release notes, and docs generated from release notes will now warn the

commit_message:
Add note for broken cinderclient versions 1.2.?

Version discovery was found to break deployments using proxies, so it was
reverted. This was introduced in python-cinderclient 1.2.0, persisted in
1.2.1 and 1.2.2, and reverted in 1.3.0 . The 1.2.? versions make note of this
in the release notes, and docs generated from release notes will now warn the
user of this.

Change-Id: Ia866dbf5f5d1c8afd7ff62b31758229f7b09bc99
Closes-Bug: #1503691

commit_message:
Change devstack to OS_PROJECT_NAME and avoid mocking oslo.policy internals

To pass the tests in gate, this commit has 2 separate changes

1) OS_TENANT_NAME is no longer used in the latest devstack, it causes all
datasource driver fail, as well as jenkins gate failure.

This fix changes devstack to use OS_PROJECT_NAME

2) Previously, we tested oslo.policy by mocking out one of the internals
of oslo.policy, just like Neutron.  Besides being improper, the newest
release of oslo.policy broke that test, which is what is blocking
the tip of master currently.

This fix shamelessly copies the fix out of Neutron, mocking out
at the layer of HTTPCheck.

Change-Id: I2a4eae714946ce98a060a43dd501b9b3619aa68e
Closes-Bug: #1505057
Closes-bug: #1505750

commit_message:
Read auth_uri from config file and remove is_public_api

1.auth_url can not be obtained from request headers, it can only
be read from config file.
2.is_public_api is not used, so let's remove it from context.

Change-Id: Ie7207ef5311e3168b64c47aef4041ed2dd0e39c6
Partially-Implements: blueprint generate-keystone-trust

commit_message:
Fix issue with su and bad kernels

Long story short, some kernels before 3.15 had an issue with using su
in a container when the network namespace was --net=host. The gate
has a 3.10 and a 3.13 kernel and has a problem with this. This changes
everything to use sudo

backport: liberty
Partially-Implements: blueprint functional-testing-gate
Change-Id: I4d79ccaa1cddffcc8393f64e7e1be2538efe33e5

commit_message:
Bump ansible to 1.9.2

Ansible 1.9.2 contains the fix needed for docker-py >1.2.0

This is needed for some gate reasons, but it is also a good version
bump because it fixes a few issues with delegate_to.

Change-Id: Iafbabb3b0232620849d0548c5cd9d8d316c2b0f3
backport: liberty
Partially-Implements: blueprint functional-testing-gate

commit_message:
Fix swarm monitor exception

In docker 1.8 (atomic-6) image, docker inspect returns Memory information
in 'HostConfig section', this patch will adopt that changes.

Depend on: I009d8034335f54063a51b8d1395ddc6891a12346
Change-Id: I63ee2393c106d59286f49f88c85c6cba0a57ae15
Closes-Bug: #1504715

commit_message:
Revert "Retire midonet-db-manage"

This partly reverts commit fb6e43c597ab25d3f27c3c751826ed1769c75682.

There seems to be compatibility requirements stronger than
i originally thought.  Let's keep this command for now
and remove it later.  It's no hurry anyway.

Change-Id: Ie54a2d3f62a520f2ac0432c78120c19220852c84

commit_message:
Make test_server work with older versions of oslo.service

Change I18a11283925369bc918002477774f196010a1bc3 fixed the test for
oslo.service >= 0.10.0, but it also broke it for older versions of
oslo.service. Since the library has minimal version of >= 0.7.0 in
requirements.txt, test should pass for those versions too.

Now, instead of validating that either reset() or restart() of workers
are triggered on SIGHUP, just validate that .start() is triggered the
expected number of times (either way, no matter how oslo.service decide
to clean up the children, they exit and then are respawned).

Change-Id: I41f9d3af780b3178b075bc1e7084f417a2bd1378
Closes-Bug: #1505645

commit_message:
Add device_id when a loadbalancer is created instead of at listener create

nova boot on lbaas_vip port is not blocked as nova throws PortInUse exception
only if the port device_id is set. Currently device_id is updated during
lbaas listener create.
This fix sets the device_id to loadbalancer id during the loadbalancer create.

Change-Id: I2dfce54322eff5f4830b94ac8424057780ebeb9d
Closes-Bug: #1482763
(cherry picked from commit f9b93a3d748ba0326883b6e50b46f3059c769c29)

commit_message:
Don't fail when data are unreadable.

When the data is corrupted, the metric cannot be processed anymore,
because msgpack raise a ValueError.

This change catches this, logs an appropriate message and create a
new empty timeserie.

Related-Bug: #1500646
Closes-Bug: #1499372
Change-Id: Ib47f84230a012197a06e615206e0b0f3e3780515

Allen, you don't need to abandon and submit a new patch when it's in merge conflict with master. You just need to rebase it and resubmit for review. The workflow I typically follow for this is:

1. in master branch, "git pull"

2. "git checkout -b merge"

3. copy the "cherry pick" download command from the gerrit interface here, for example for this patch (for me)

  "git fetch ssh://richard@review.openstack.org:29418/openstack/horizon refs/changes/78/225378/1 && git cherry-pick FETCH_HEAD"

4. check merge conflicts with "git status"

5. edit merge conflicts, for example:

   vi openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/volumes/volume_types/forms.py
   git add vi openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/volumes/volume_types/forms.py

6. "git commit"

7. check the "git log" to ensure you've only got one commit on the top of master

8. "git review -f"   (the -f removes the temporary "merge" branch so you can reuse it later)'}, {'account_id': 14151, 'date': '2015-09-21 01:13:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Improve error message for creating QoS Spec

When input a "QoS Spec" name that already exists in "create
QoS Spec" modal form, we will see the error message:
"Unable to create QoS Spec" in the top right corner of the
page, this error message is not specific and clear. If we
provide specific and clear error message: 'QoS Spec name "%s"
already exists.' beside the name field, it will be more better.

Change-Id: I3aed7b39fb7f3e991738ad246585af68314a0cf3
Closes-Bug: #1494166

commit_message:
Replaced deprecated isotime() function

The agents_db.py was using a deprecated function 'isotime()'.

I removed the deprecated function and replaced it with:
datetime.datetime.isoformat()

https://docs.python.org/2/library/datetime.html

Change-Id: I32b6096fb1a42caef529db0a71fa52f7de5706f5
Closes-Bug: #1504557

commit_message:
Moves an incorrectly marked negative test

The following test had been marked as negative by mistake. This commits
moves it back to the positive test file.

commit_message:
Add failure ports to error message

On the gate, test_dualnet_multi_prefix_slaac fails due to duplicated
ports on the test. However, the error message doesn't contain actual
ports information. This patch adds it for debugging.

Change-Id: I198ae97b954c01581a037923494949527fed8efa
Related-Bug: #1505478

Hi Sheng,

Thanks for you reply, you mentioned this bug only affects in Kilo/Juno, does this mean I shouldn't fix this bug in current master branch? Sorry I'm a newbie."}, {'account_id': 8290, 'date': '2015-09-15 06:38:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

the bug is found in Kilo Ceilometer, but in Liberty, we have move pipeline process to notification-agent, the polling agent will will send all samples to notification-agent, and notification will publish samples to pipeline. this is different with before. so I think the check is needed in current implementation.'}, {'account_id': 13560, 'date': '2015-09-15 17:16:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

I think in Liberty, the polling agent still checks the pipeline source [1], so polling tasks are launched only for matched meters (from each pipeline source) which I think means that notification agent check for supported samples from polling agent is redundant.

This also implies that the notification agent pipeline sources should include the polling agent pipeline sources for publishing of polled samples to succeed.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/ceilometer/blob/master/ceilometer/agent/base.py#L320'}, {'account_id': 13248, 'date': '2015-09-16 08:45:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hi Rohit,

Thanks for your guidance. As notification agent check for supported samples from polling agent is redundant,
I think we can add some code in SamplePipeline.publish_data() method to check whether the samples come from
polling agent, if so, the support check can be skipped. 
However, it seems currently there's no information about the generator in Sample instance. I'm not sure is it
possible to add a property in ceilometer.Sample(e.g. generator_id) to indicate the generator of the sample instance.
Then in ceilometer.agent.base.PollingTask.poll_and_notify() method, the polling agent can set the generator_id of
samples as "ceilomter.agent.base.PollingTask"(or something else) to indicate this sample is generated by polling task.'}, {'account_id': 13248, 'date': '2015-09-17 10:49:22.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 13248, 'date': '2015-09-17 10:57:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

When polling agent send samples in notification, it will set the 'event_type' property of the notification as 'telemetry.polling', see [1]. So I think we can use the 'event_type' property to judge whether the sample come from polling agent or not, if so, we can skip the support check in sample pipeline.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/ceilometer/blob/master/ceilometer/agent/base.py#L202"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-17 11:43:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

commit_message:
Remove duplicated pipeline support meter check

When publishing samples with sample pipeline, it will check
the samples supported by the source definition of the pipeline
or not. But the samples from polling agent are always supported
by the pipeline because when setup polling tasks, the pollster
had been checked and matched corresponding pipeline. This check
has no affect of the publishing result if the sample come from
polling agent, but will cost cpu resources if we have a complex
pipeline definition. This commit add code in sample pipeline to
check the sample come from polling agent or not, if so, the
support check will be skipped.

Closes-Bug: #1494156
Change-Id: Ibda459ee688b250134bd03116f86c0c4a6d7c5c5

commit_message:
Bump minimum tempest-lib version

Now we(Tempest team) are migrating common part of Tempest to tempest-lib
for running Tempest-like test on each project repository.
That work requires the latest tempest-lib. So this patch bumps minimum
tempest-lib version.

Change-Id: I516d4119fd200c79a8be4598cbb0d732344e8b75

started to fail because of usage of not strict constructions.

commit_message:
Fix usage of dependencies

Manila is broken is threee places, so fix them:
1) test 'test_misc' with WebOb 1.5

WebOb 1.5 was released at 2015-10-11. With this new version,
webob.exc.WSGIHTTPException() constructor now fails with a KeyError
when the HTTP status code is 0.

test_exceptions_raise() of test_misc tries to instantiate all
exceptions of manila.exception. The problem is that
ConvertedException uses a default HTTP status code of 0.

Modify the default HTTP status code of ConvertedException to 400 to
fix the unit tests.

2) Add dependency for 'testresources' that is required by migration
tests.

3) Remove 2 unit tests related to testing of oslo.policy lib
functionality that should not be tested in Manila. It started failing
because under-the-hood behaviour was changed in new realese 0.12.0

Closes-Bug: #1505153
Closes-Bug: #1505374

(cherry picked from commit 9c99814ce5943bd4c33bf3650b832666e31b3411)

-- squashed with another change to get tests to pass on stable/liberty --

Fix broken unit tests

With release of six module version 1.10.0 several our unit tests
started to fail because of usage of not strict constructions.

Changes:
1) Manila unit test
"manila.tests.share.test_api.ShareAPITestCase.test_extend_quota_error"
used str for int substitution. So, use int data for int substitution.

2) Module 'manila.share.drivers.hp.hp_3par_mediator' was using
LOG.exception function when no traceback were exist it led to
AttributeError on py34. So, replace all usages of 'LOG.exception'
with 'LOG.error' where no raised exceptions exist.

Change-Id: Ic5b37bfb9d939d03f6ff68bc53d134bf9e5f996e
Closes-Bug: #1503969
(cherry picked from commit f38b8d4efd1f68f4ea29747f7377e0936f61d89c)

--

Change-Id: I0f28f3c3fb2c7eec1bafc3a617344990f86810cf

commit_message:
Change camelCase to snake_case in JSON

The Java Persister converts camelCase to snake_case for
the alarm state transition sub_alarms JSON element.

The python persister needs to do the same.

The following element names in the alarm state transition
sub_alarm element need to be converted to snake_case:

subAlarmExpression -> sub_alarm_expression
metricDefinition -> metric_definition
alarmState -> alarm_state

These elements originate from the Monasca Threshold Engine.
Ideally, the Threshold Engine should be modified to send
the JSON in snake_case.

Change-Id: I33c779e4741c797fbeeaf179441a65504444b0bd

Hi Samuel,
Please find a little explanation of these methods:

im_func which returns the (unbound) function object
im_self which returns the object the function is bound to (class instance)

Basically, im_self attribute of a bound method changes, to allow using it as the parameter when calling function. It's usefulness could be considered when using a classmethod.

In python 3 these methods are deprecated and replaced."}, {'account_id': 14867, 'date': '2015-07-17 18:21:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Python3: do not use im_self/im_func/func_closure

Use __self__, __func__ and __closure__ instead, as they work
with both Python 2 and 3.

Modifying usage of __func__ in codebase.

Change-Id: I57e907c28c1d4646605e70194ea3650806730b83

commit_message:
Updates the lint check to ignore templates

This change is needed because some python files being checked
by the flake8 check will have jinja2 expressions within them
which will cause flake syntax failures.

Change-Id: Id9291c2c1c9ab2632f5fd9b94e13fa4eb62eb05e
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Use inventory instead of hostfile parameter

The hostfile parameter in ansible.cfg is deprecated per documentation:
http://docs.ansible.com/ansible/intro_configuration.html#hostfile

This small patch update the hostfile parameter to inventory

Change-Id: I16a63c728d59799d70d2d1414aacf9a17eafcfb5
(cherry picked from commit 50851d55f90b66627b95517a94dbf9872f2859a9)

commit_message:
Use value_specs for port_security_enabled flag

 * Change the Heat template to use value_specs to specify the
   port_security_enabled flag so that it works with kilo and future
   releases

Change-Id: I3bc3956761221608ee746faad92d82b040a8823b
Closes-Bug: 1503984

commit_message:
Bump minimum tempest-lib version

Now we(Tempest team) are migrating common part of Tempest to tempest-lib
for running Tempest-like test on each project repository.
That work requires the latest tempest-lib. So this patch bumps minimum
tempest-lib version.

NOTE (gmann) - Tempest-lib req should be updated on each stable branch as
Tempest is branchless and need to support all stable branches.

Change-Id: I9e6c6d2fd1e83247bc170d1cbdaa91593919d14b
(cherry picked from commit fcc5bfb7e5af4173743bb4412cd8bc8c49487153)

commit_message:
Add jsonschema helper utility

Add a small utility function on-top of jsonschema that
handles tuples and lists correctly, this is likely useful
for others as well to use.

Change-Id: Ib4794d5e29bd63ee7c3a4d58abea1913e5aecada

commit_message:
Scope requests to horizon scoped region

Instead of adding region to all requests by default if not
specified, we'll instead honor a region of 'INJECT_REGION'.
This is because not all environments add region as a dimension
for metrics, so we can't do this by default.

Change-Id: I126cd604b3b6d84d0f4efa5dc99aa538e6cf0d77
Closes-Bug: #1494337

In another patch we've also include a default whitelist for the set of metrics collected. commit_message:
Add the akloadbalancerstatus API extension and lbaasv2 plugin

This is a Neutron API extension + plugin to allow updating of LB
status via API.

To enable, in neutron.conf:

Add the full python path to service_plugins, ie:

service_plugins=...,akanda.neutron.plugins.lbaas_neutron_plugin.LoadBalancerPluginv2

Ensure api_extensions_path contains the paths to both this repo's extensions,
as well as upstream neutron-lbaas extensions.

Change-Id: I00b921c6bcd8c5d8478e0d9f3e7b0967af6b1fcc

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 18401, 'date': '2015-09-29 15:45:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Nice work, BTW.

I have just one general question/suggestion about monitor delay (currently "boot_wait" option). Would it be useful to implement monitor delay configuration in VNFD template under each monitor policy? Like this for example:

 ...
 monitoring_policy:
   ping:
+    monitoring_delay: 60
     monitoring_params: 30
       count: 2
 ...

That would mean that monitoring will start 60 seconds after boot, so it is basically a current "boot_wait" parameter. This option will be even more useful for monitoring related to auto-scaling, since different VMs can have different startup times for their functions etc...

Or this should be handled by individual monitor drivers? What do you think?'}, {'account_id': 16511, 'date': '2015-09-30 00:33:15.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 11.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-30 00:38:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-tacker-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/84/224384/11/check/gate-tacker-pep8/52d869e/ : SUCCESS in 1m 16s'}, {'account_id': 16511, 'date': '2015-09-30 01:19:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

@Luka - I like the idea of specifying the monitoring delay along with the policy.  The only issue is that the monitoring_policy is specified at the VDU level and the boot_wait logic is happening at the Device level.  So the logic could certainly happen in the driver, since it has access to the boot_at time in the hosting_device dict.  We also talked about having a device-level monitoring_policy that would be inherited by the VDU policies, so maybe this is a good example of that. Bob - tried the patchset with ping monitor. It works like a charm! 

One observation though, the driver reports failure even on *one* ping cmd failure. This too aggressive IMO. I remember one of the earlier tacker demo we did waits for N consecutive ping failure before reporting a failure event up. This will help to avoid unnecessarily tripping health-mon respawn due some transient network failures.'}, {'account_id': 13380, 'date': '2015-10-09 22:26:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

One comment on the latest patchset ...'}, {'account_id': 16511, 'date': '2015-10-10 18:19:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 18:

(1 comment)

Will change LogOnly to not mark DEAD.  Re: the ping operation, I copied the old behavior so it's doing whatever it did before.  ping is going to return 1 or 2 instead of 0 if there are any failures, and we can't maintain state across driver invocations (yet) so I'm not sure how to allow it to fail intermittently and still pass the condition.  How many ping failures do we allow and do we need to require N successful pings in a row before we consider it successful?  Driver could certainly call the ping command several times and require a completely successful ping sequence before it returns success.  But that takes time away from other drivers too."}, {'account_id': 13380, 'date': '2015-10-10 21:25:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)

On the ping I tried the old code and it had the same behavior. So it is fair to take any ping enhancements (if any) in a separate patchset instead of this framework level change. 

Looks good now, thanks for your patience. commit_message:
Implement Monitoring Framework

 * Changes the monitor function to use a loadable driver

 * Changes the monitoring thread to use a re-entrant lock
   (RLock()) to prevent it from blocking itself during
    recovery actions

Change-Id: Icf40ffd3123f3b804de16c88164d84077fbf28e2
Implements: blueprint health-monitoring
Closes-Bug: 1497474

commit_message:
Mock keystone call to avoid test failure

The test test_password_prompted() was expecting a keystone failure, but
because of an error in the requests/urllib3 library it was returning a
different exception and causing our tests to fail, see[1].

Independent of the the problem above on tests we should not rely on some
external library failing like that, we should mock this failures to make
our tests more reliable and that's what this patch is doing.

[1] https://bugs.launchpad.net/ospurge/+bug/1503768

Change-Id: I3e6091eb2bc221a16fdc18b998ba138058818894
Closes-Bug: #1504197

code-review guidelines: add checklist for config options

The code-review guidelines document should be a somewhat agreed list
of what to consider when doing a review. This patch set adds the
items to check if the review contains changes which involves config
options.

Metadefs have no 'name' field (because they use namespace),
which matches their data, but since name will likely be a
common sort field it will potentially cause problems with sort.

When doing cross resource searching on name (no type specified),
the current queries result in zero results being returned if
1) OS::Glance::Metadef are specified first or
2) no types are specified (the server automatically adds all the

Closes-Bug: #1501123

commit_message:
Fix for no name field in metadef namespace

Metadefs have no 'name' field (because they use namespace),
which matches their data, but since name will likely be a
common sort field it will potentially cause problems with sort.

When doing cross resource searching on name (no type specified),
the current queries result in zero results being returned if
1) OS::Glance::Metadef are specified first or
2) no types are specified (the server automatically adds all the
   types to the query to elasticsearch.

Change-Id: I05b26c951ea6d0df890878d40d5113d87af08754
Closes-Bug: #1501123

commit_message:
Add subunit output for devstack on failure

This commit adds saving a devstack event when we trip the exit_trap.
This will save a similar result to the stream in the successful case,
but instead mark it as a failure.

Change-Id: If49ffe427f8b1aa0b0ab25d9ca84bace468b9966

"}, {'created': '2015-10-01 15:44:43.000000000', 'message': "Update Glance to Liberty RC1

This patch includes the following updates based on the updated source in
Glance's Liberty release:
 - glance-api-paste.ini
 - glance-registry-paste.ini
 - policy.json

The following defaults have their values changed based on new defaults for the
Liberty release. Note that any user_variables.yml values that have been set to
customise these will need to be reviewed and adjusted accordingly for liberty.
 - glance_digest_algorithm

Note also that the glance_swift_store_auth_version has been set to use '3' as
the default, meaning that it will use Keystone's v3 API as the default.

TODO:
 - Figure out how to use swift_store_config_file as it has replaced the way
   that Keystone auth is done here.
 - Go through ALL the .conf files properly.

DocImpact
UpgradeImpact
Implements: blueprint liberty-release
Change-Id: I2f58c0dbdb3ee55c0a4792df6e7b5b15aa8f0b01
"}, {'created': '2015-10-01 15:46:09.000000000', 'message': "Update Glance to Liberty RC1

This patch includes the following updates based on the updated source in
Glance's Liberty release:
 - glance-api-paste.ini
 - glance-registry-paste.ini
 - policy.json

The following defaults have their values changed based on new defaults for the
Liberty release. Note that any user_variables.yml values that have been set to
customise these will need to be reviewed and adjusted accordingly for liberty.
 - glance_digest_algorithm

Note also that the glance_swift_store_auth_version has been set to use '3' as
the default, meaning that it will use Keystone's v3 API as the default.

New configurable options:
 - glance_swift_store_auth_version
   This is the Keystone API auth version to use. The previous default
   was 2, but this patch changes it to 3.

 - glance_swift_store_user_domain
   This is the Domain ID for the user used to authenticate to Swift.

 - glance_swift_store_project_domain
   This is the Domain ID for the project used to authenticate to Swift.

TODO:
 - Figure out how to use swift_store_config_file as it has replaced the way
   that Keystone auth is done here.
 - Go through ALL the .conf files properly.

DocImpact
UpgradeImpact
Implements: blueprint liberty-release
Co-Authored-By: Ian Cordasco <graffatcolmingov@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I2f58c0dbdb3ee55c0a4792df6e7b5b15aa8f0b01

commit_message:
Update Glance Configuration for Liberty

This patch includes the following updates based on the updated source in
Glance's Liberty release:
 - glance-api-paste.ini
 - glance-api.conf
 - glance-registry-paste.ini
 - glance-registry.conf
 - glance-cache.conf
 - glance-manage.conf
 - glance-scrubber.conf

The following defaults have their values changed based on new defaults for the
Liberty release. Note that any user_variables.yml values that have been set to
customise these will need to be reviewed and adjusted accordingly for liberty.
 - glance_digest_algorithm

Note also that the glance_swift_store_auth_version has been set to use '3' as
the default, meaning that it will use Keystone's v3 API as the default.

New configurable options:
 - glance_swift_store_auth_version
   This is the Keystone API auth version to use. The previous default
   was 2, but this patch changes it to 3.

 - glance_swift_store_user_domain
   This is the Domain ID for the user used to authenticate to Swift.

 - glance_swift_store_project_domain
   This is the Domain ID for the project used to authenticate to Swift.

Note that the policy.json file included is not the same as the upstream
default. Changes have been included which improve the security of image
publication and image group membership.

DocImpact
UpgradeImpact
Closes-Bug: #1479131
Implements: blueprint liberty-release
Co-Authored-By: Ian Cordasco <graffatcolmingov@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I2f58c0dbdb3ee55c0a4792df6e7b5b15aa8f0b01

[{'created': '2015-10-08 18:07:59.000000000', 'message': "Install spice-html5 from source

'ws://' is currently hardcoded within the spice_auto.html file included
in the packaged release of spice-html5, raising a security error when
accessing consoles over HTTPS.

Remove the existing apt package and install spice-html5 from source
instead since this issue has been corrected as of spice-html5-0.1.6.

commit_message:
Install spice-html5 from source

'ws://' is currently hardcoded within the spice_auto.html file included
in the packaged release of spice-html5, raising a security error when
accessing consoles over HTTPS.

Remove the existing apt package and install spice-html5 from source
instead since this issue has been corrected as of spice-html5-0.1.6.

Change-Id: Ie308a477143037963f903f2ac21b2b1f0328fcb3
Partial-Bug: #1424797
(cherry picked from commit a944d049fb14380e81692c19267c2eec443c386a)

commit_message:
Fix 'glance details' command in Operation Guide

'glance details' is not used any more. We should use
'glance image-show' instead.

Change-Id: Idc63a0783377bc2528300da0e52c6a6a727cf597
Closes-bug: #1505179

commit_message:
Fix for no name field in metadef namespace

Metadefs have no 'name' field (because they use namespace),
which matches their data, but since name will likely be a
common sort field it will potentially cause problems with sort.

When doing cross resource searching on name (no type specified),
the current queries result in zero results being returned if
1) OS::Glance::Metadef are specified first or
2) no types are specified (the server automatically adds all the
   types to the query to elasticsearch.

Change-Id: I05b26c951ea6d0df890878d40d5113d87af08754
Closes-Bug: #1501123

Why not really, really future-proof the process and de-couple from an event with a particular time box? We could tie it to:
- geographical location of a contributor plucked at random from our database
- geographical location of the nth contribution of a prior release, from which cloud computer/laptop location
- headquarters of the nth organization contributing to OpenStack (could be random selection)

Summits and their location are important but we don't know if they'll always be every six months, if they'll always be at a location rather than remote, and the timeboxing of summits is really limiting our planning. Let's correlate with something that won't change in the future as long as OpenStack has contributors and contributions. The fun part can be random selection."}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-10-12 23:26:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

honestly, because I am bored talking about this already. :)

commit_message:
remove naming timebox restriction

There is no reason to hold off on naming releases one we know their
location. And holding off on release naming is more likely to create
confusion where the dev community just picks a placeholder, uses it in
communication, and that placeholder is wrong later.

Especially as projects are now moving into a phase of planning for
multiple releases in advance for larger efforts, the current
restriction just adds confusion and cleanup work later.

Change-Id: Ife143447ff4a6d2d85260fd9d889853863eff272

commit_message:
Select Thierry Carrez as TC chair for Mitaka

The chair is responsible for making sure meetings are held
according to the rules described in our charter, and for
communicating the decisions taken during those meetings to the
Board of Directors and the OpenStack community at large.

Change-Id: I8cf96ee2928f99e3fea8ff4e8a66f26fc8bcd16c

commit_message:
Fix the nodepool file check

The check was meant to verify two things:
 - the nodepool file exists
 - the nodepool file is not zero size

Combining them doesn't work, though, so this was never executing
as intended. This patch fixes that.

Conflicts:
------scripts/gate-check-commit.sh

Change-Id: I7a192614afb00d11de1fd944ff20c0c89223f5c3
(cherry picked from commit affb541c3f0966f686c18dd10ddb640e4686449d)

commit_message:
Fixing help string for octavia.conf option

The controller_ip_port_list help string is misdocumented as
it suggests using enclosing your ip:port list with '[', ']' which
is incorrect as it will cause the parser to concatinate '[' on your
first item and ']' on your second item.

Change-Id: I5ae9a2013264585f00ec3292ead56162cdf2c8ea

commit_message:
Block/cap incompatible libraries

This updates the global requirements to block requests 2.8.0 due to:
  https://launchpad.net/bugs/1476770 and
  https://launchpad.net/bugs/1503768 and
  https://launchpad.net/bugs/1505326

And also blocks oslo.messaging 2.6.0 temporarily due to:
  https://launchpad.net/bugs/1505295

And also blocks oslo.versionedobjects 0.11.0 temporarily due to:
  https://launchpad.net/bugs/1505677

And also blocks WebOb<1.5.0 temporarily due to:
  https://launchpad.net/bugs/1505153

Related-Bug: #1476770
Related-Bug: #1503768
Related-Bug: #1505326
Related-Bug: #1505295
Related-Bug: #1505153
Related-Bug: #1505677
Change-Id: I3aabbf717ef21a41c7bb9d21957df838642926f0

commit_message:
Add basic Fedora 22 support to yum-minimal

Add basic F22/dnf support to yum-minimal path.  We duplicate the
existing yum path and make some changes for installing dnf (we also
install yum, but that's just a wrapper to dnf).

This works just fine, and is the first step along the way to the
cleanups done in If4bd5f88e26bd6f2168958f1ec1efff1072de7ba

Change-Id: I80b35dc36153d185f3d7982a7391c3bc2bed2aa1

commit_message:
Fix SolidFire target composition

We added the target composition a while back but never
really finished it.  We created a set of interface methods
and had them call the target class mostly thinking we'd
want this when adding FC.

It turns out that doing a regular composition and using
get_attr will actually work fine when the FC target is
added, so re factor this and make it a true composition
where both objects inherit attributes from each other.

Change-Id: I1da439c2e50ec66d759def19d3eda997797d00a5

commit_message:
Suppress Exceptions on L3 Packet IN

Exceptions on L3 packet in might cause the entire application
to exist, add a defensive try/except to avoid these cases

Change-Id: I01b2b5d568c506cf456a9508e1d2b1f20e0c44aa

commit_message:
Add cleanup functionality to OVS bridge

Clean ports from bridge on unstack, this is currently not needed
as we uninstall OVS version anyway, but is good for the future
when we dont want to install/uninstall the host OVS version.

Change-Id: I8eacb11d34eb0b9b06e58f075e1a80e049294189

The NPIV port mapping code can be tricky to debug.  This change provides
a small, but significant logging change that enables easier debug.  This
may help with concurrency issues that may arise when deploying many
Cinder volumes at once.

Change-Id: I7d80848266bf83f1febfc3089e6e1e057df1ffa5

commit_message:
Increase logging in NPIV port mappings

The NPIV port mapping code can be tricky to debug.  This change provides
a small, but significant logging change that enables easier debug.  This
may help with concurrency issues that may arise when deploying many
Cinder volumes at once.

Change-Id: I7d80848266bf83f1febfc3089e6e1e057df1ffa5

[{'created': '2015-09-25 20:32:35.000000000', 'message': "jq 1.5 support

According the JSON spec, the \n character should be encoded. That's a
policy that jq 1.5 enforce.

Because of that, it's not possible anymore the generate a JSON file with
the content of the private key without dropping the \n.

Without this patch, we get the following error:
parse error: Invalid string: control characters from U+0000 through
U+001F must be escaped at line 32, column 30

Change-Id: Id4a956443ff8c99f76a5778ed5c3a53367c8e408

parse error: Invalid string: control characters from U+0000 through
U+001F must be escaped at line 32, column 30

Change-Id: Id4a956443ff8c99f76a5778ed5c3a53367c8e408
Depends-On: I8ab2d691b2789e7f7e9931d67e9905b34fbba56
"}]
commit_message:
jq 1.5 support

According the JSON spec, the \n character should be encoded. That's a
policy that jq 1.5 enforce.

Because of that, it's not possible anymore the generate a JSON file with
the content of the private key without dropping the \n.

Without this patch, we get the following error:
parse error: Invalid string: control characters from U+0000 through
U+001F must be escaped at line 32, column 30

Change-Id: Id4a956443ff8c99f76a5778ed5c3a53367c8e408
Depends-On: I8ab2d691b2789e7f7e9931d67e9905b34fbba56

commit_message:
Omnibus stable/liberty fix

There are currently 3 different blocking issues in stable/liberty due
to library releases: webob 1.5, oslo.db 3.0.0, and
oslo.versionedobjects 0.11.0. This is a squashed fix for all of them
as none can land without the others.

Issue #1 - oslo.db

Add testresources used by oslo.db fixture

If we use oslo.db fixtures, we'll need the package or
the next version of oslo.db release will break us.

(Cherry-picked from 4bcc26487837b7ece7797f88622dea1b6d09bd94)

Closes-Bug: #1503501

Issue #2 - oslo.versionedobjects

Drop unused obj_to_primitive() override

This was a band-aid override until o.vo gained the obj_relationships fix
that this method overrides. That has been in place since o.vo 0.8.0, which
means this is long since no longer necessary (and is actually blocking our
ability to absorb bug fixes to this code in o.vo). Further, we no longer
use this directly because we're doing backports based on version manifests,
which means we no longer consult child_versions _or_ obj_relationships.

(cherry picked from commit 142f1d9cc4ace90956c665c40b1f78795f9f7e29)

Issue #3 - webob

Default ConvertedException code to 500

webob 1.5.0 released on 10/11 has change f6c749011 which
strictly enforces status codes in exceptions, and 0 is not
a valid status code so tests fail.

Change the default to 500 to match the default in the parent
class in webob.

Closes-Bug: #1505153
(cherry picked from commit 10438c0fc34bd088e018e1a5e8ec57b396528792)

Change-Id: I1e06e77308a7dd23209124f0807d61fb52470188

commit_message:
Remove 'not_analyzed' from server.name

Remove 'not_analyzed' from server name. In general,
not_analyzed should only be used for id fields and those where it
doesn't make sense to tokenize values.

Change-Id: I35bff3a422d1a809b461e3f1fdf162e2fb1c5f24
Closes-Bug: #1505358

- gate-bandit-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/61/221861/3/check/gate-bandit-python27/27f7ceb/ : SUCCESS in 1m 37s'}, {'account_id': 11861, 'date': '2015-09-09 17:22:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Very cool change!  Performance improvement is beyond noticeable.  

I agree: let's just do sensible default behavior with respect to cores.

A couple of issues I'm getting in testing:

1) this error outputs once for each thread:
    [general_hardcoded_password]	WARNING	Using relative path for word_list: ./wordlist/default-passwords

2) Severity filtering doesn't seem to work"}, {'account_id': 1528, 'date': '2015-09-10 11:19:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(10 comments)

A lot of comments about details, but I like the patch in general. For testing, I don't think anything really changes. If you want to make sure things are reproducible in normal tests, you can always mock Pool.map to "return [func(x) for x in iterable]"

For progress, the map_async callback could be good. It would need a message queue back to the main process and the main process would have to somehow poll on both that and results being available at the same time.'}, {'account_id': 11029, 'date': '2015-09-10 16:30:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Useful comments, thanks Stan.  I'll address them more specifically in a future patchset.

This map_async() with a p.get(unrealistically_long_timeout) call is a pattern that I've used in a few personal projects, to workaround http://bugs.python.org/issue8296.  It's based on the last example at http://bryceboe.com/2010/08/26/python-multiprocessing-and-keyboardinterrupt/.

He does a better job of describing the problem with a simple Pool.map() call that the pattern works around.  "First, while the worker processes can handle the KeyboardInterrupt and call sys.exit, these processes persist and thus receive future tasks. Second, the KeyboardInterrupt is not delivered to the parent process until all jobs are completed."

The map_async() / get() pattern lets Control-C terminate the program immediately, rather than continuing to execute worker processes.'}, {'account_id': 11861, 'date': '2015-09-21 06:57:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2

OK, I think this has sat long enough.  I'm happy to introduce this and make further enhancements to it in future patchsets."}, {'account_id': 11861, 'date': '2015-09-22 11:58:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: -Code-Review

Stan brings up some good points, let's wrap those up before we merge this"}, {'account_id': 11029, 'date': '2015-09-22 17:14:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 1528, 'date': '2015-09-23 01:45:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Introduce concurrent testing with multiprocessing

On my Macbook Pro (~2012 2.9GHz Intel Core i7 - four logical cores),
with multiprocessing:
$ time bandit -r ~/repo/nova ~/repo/glance ~/repo/keystone
real    0m33.926s
user    1m52.437s
sys 0m0.787s

Using current bandit master without multiprocessing:
$ time bandit -r ~/repo/nova ~/repo/glance ~/repo/keystone
real    1m11.314s
user    1m10.613s
sys     0m0.529s

Minimal refactoring was performed - some BanditManager logic was moved
from instance-level to class-level functions to allow them to be passed
into multiprocessing map_async() with minimal complexity. The progress
indicator displayed during interactive runs was also killed to keep the
solution simple.

To discuss:
 - Testing?  (For a start, it passes all current tox tests.)
 - Make sure we're okay with default behavior (I personally quite like
   not having to think about it :) ), or consider multiprocessing
   elements that might be tweaked or made optional.
 - Look at options for bringing back progress indicator, although I'm
   wondering if that will be missed.

Change-Id: I0370d617a2cf17444ee91d7a3dc8117d7ffc2ad7

commit_message:
Add basic metric generation and associated tests

This commit adds basic metric generation to Bandit. Specifically, it
counts LOC and #nosec instances associated with a run.  It also exposes
a total count of issues identified, by severity & confidence level.

It includes functional testing against several existing example scripts.

It does *not* do anything with the results other than send them to the
logger.debug() facility.  Inclusion in Bandit output formats is left for
a separate commit.

There are also quite likely additional metrics that we will want to add
at a future date.

Change-Id: I649b2214bef81df6042986dfa9b03e57c195b0e1

commit_message:
Fix incorrect usage of assertEqual() in some tests

Incorrect usage of assertEqual() method is found in some tests:
"assertEqual(True, ...)".
The correct way is to use "assertTrue(...)" in such cases.

This commit will substitute all occurences of "assertEqual(True, ...)"
in tests to correct form: "assertTrue(...)".

Change-Id: I1ad9ce1299e67c4c649fa7b05b245c5ad4496f43
Closes-Bug: 1504368

commit_message:
FIX TypeError for list queue command.

Scenario: pooling is enabled but no pool present in the env.
Zaqar list queues command through a type error with 
a response code 500.

Change-Id: I3b008b83e8fb1c85a5d7e21c7aad83e66a5ffa89
Closes-Bug: #1502042

commit_message:
dbsync should only notify services that use the db

When db-sync is run, only services that that talk to the database need
to be restarted.  This introduces a new tag for that type of services
(neturon-db-sync-service).  Currently only neutron-server talks to mysql
directly, so it is the only service with this tag applied.

Change-Id: I0ac15865b408fe9acb643e800836da8b3eeb7827

Phil, it's not obvious to me why the existing behavior is incorrect on Ironic and your proposed behavior is. I'm sure you're right, and I'm sure it's a only-one-guest-per-node sort of thing. However, can you expand the comments to explain it a little more?"}, {'account_id': 9420, 'date': '2015-02-03 01:45:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Looks like we would end up here: https://github.com/drkjam/netaddr/blob/rel-0.7.x/netaddr/ip/__init__.py#L309-L320 and end up with and AddrFormatError.  Is that what you are seeing Phil?'}, {'account_id': 1501, 'date': '2015-02-11 17:40:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Hi Dan,

The issue is that in the case of a virt diver host_ip is a meaningful part of the host state, as it tells you something about where the VM is going to be scheduled to (and for this particular filter that's important).    

But for a nova-compute host that's being used as a proxy to Ironic the host_ip is meaningless since it has nothing to do with the physical server you're going to get (any kind of affinity scheduling is meaningless to Ironic).  So it doesn't feel right to force the Ironic driver to include a host_ip value in the host state it returns, hence this filter needs to treat that as an optional field and check it exists before it tries to read it."}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2015-02-25 16:02:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

(2 comments)

I guess I'm not sure I agree with the assertion that affinity doesn't make sense with Ironic. If anything, network affinity is the *only* kind that *does* make sense with Ironic, right? It seems like this is maybe another reason why the current way Ironic represents itself in nova is broken. Anyway, probably not worth blocking this patch at this point since it was already half doing this behavior.

However, I do think some copious comments (and in the proper location) are warranted to explain what is going on here."}, {'account_id': 1501, 'date': '2015-03-02 16:19:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-29 14:05:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2015-08-12 07:16:43.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

This patch has been stalled for a long time, so I am abandoning it. Please feel free to restore it when the code is ready for review.'}, {'account_id': 9452, 'date': '2015-10-13 17:18:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I'm many days late to the party here but

>Whilst it doesn't make sense to use this filter with Ironic

 I came across this patch while working to solve an internal use case. Our HPCC/Hadoop teams have certain scenarios where they need to ensure that certain compute workloads are in the same rack to minimize cross-fabric traffic.

 In a really small environment it's probably not a big deal to manually select which host you want to use, but in our case we need to be able to turn up thousands of machines in a short period of time, and ensure that certain groups of machines are in the same rack. We keep these hosts in an L3 environment. So in this case SimpleCIDRAffinityFilter would do this for us."}]

commit_message:
Make SimpleCIDRAffinityFilter accept missing host_ip

The SimpleCIDRAffinityFilter uses the host_ip value from host_state,
but the ironic driver doesn't provide this value. Whilst it doesn't
make sense to use this filter with Ironic nodes, it should be possible
to have in configured in system configured to use both ironic and a
virt driver. This change makes the filter always pass if there is no
host_ip value.

Closes-bug: 1401121
Change-Id: I9b7b8f5abd0d3e4a2d4347fa876aee2abf43c2d9

This was not included in the main driver patch that landed,
this adds it and allows rug-ctl to work generically across
drivers.

commit_message:
Fix bad string replacement

In a previous patch, some bad string replacement messed up config
registration, causing error_cooldown to stop working. This fixes it
and updates the instance_manager to inherit the RugTestBase, which
would have caught the issue in test. This also requires a couple
of minor tweaks to existing tests.

Change-Id: I7146f779d69a1b0cde6c30f0afa81d89553bd0d9

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-10 04:42:36.000000000', 'message': "Fix wsgi_script entry point

Previously the wsgi_script openstack-health entry point was pointing
directly to flask app object in the api module. However the script
constructed by pbr attempts to call app and set that as the
application for mod_wsgi. However this is the incorrect usage for a
flask app, and will fail because the app object isn't expected to be
called by itself without any args) Also, according to the flask docs
[1] you just need to set the flask app as the application var in the
to run with mod_wsgi. This commit fixes the wsgi_script entrypoint by
creating a wrapper function which can be called by the generated
output of wsgi scripts from pbr and will return the flask app. This
function is then used as the wsgi_script entrypoint instead of the app
itself. Additionally, this also gives a good injection point if there
are any future initialization or configuration steps that need to be
taken when running.

[1] http://flask.pocoo.org/docs/0.10/deploying/mod_wsgi/#creating-a-wsgi-file

Change-Id: I6e49b4dbbe58e054a28412207b99eb2982a45fbe
"}]
commit_message:
Fix wsgi_script entry point

Previously the wsgi_script openstack-health entry point was pointing
directly to flask app object in the api module. However the script
constructed by pbr attempts to call app and set that as the
application for mod_wsgi. However this is the incorrect usage for a
flask app, and will fail because the app object isn't expected to be
called by itself without any args) Also, according to the flask docs
[1] you just need to set the flask app as the application var in the
to run with mod_wsgi. This commit fixes the wsgi_script entrypoint by
creating a wrapper function which can be called by the generated
output of wsgi scripts from pbr and will return the flask app. This
function is then used as the wsgi_script entrypoint instead of the app
itself. Additionally, this also gives a good injection point if there
are any future initialization or configuration steps that need to be
taken when running.

[1] http://flask.pocoo.org/docs/0.10/deploying/mod_wsgi/#creating-a-wsgi-file

Change-Id: I6e49b4dbbe58e054a28412207b99eb2982a45fbe

 /var/cache/dnf/updates-d28e3be95240972f/packages/

where i'm not sure how it has decided on the layout

i don't know the answers atm ... i'm actually thinking we might need to run an instance of squid or something infront of our updates.

commit_message:
Use dnf download to cache packages

Under fedora 22, dnf does not use the --downloadonly flag.  It has
switched to 'dnf download'.

Change-Id: Iadb41317a1ad217a9b90c015d22a09ee214c4594
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <pabelanger@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Try new ChefDK 9.0

Since it's early for us in the M release, we could consider upgrading
ChefDK.  This patch is a test run for that.  Probably need a test run
for the Repo as well before making a decision.

Cleanup minor unit test warning

Change-Id: I9dd80cd10ac0eacfc7146eec48d862dc2f3d7dc2

commit_message:
Drop consoleauth and novncproxy

There is no need to configure these services because
Ironic doesn't currently support them.

Change-Id: Iaa41ab18a834dbbca03b3d8f190c815d50cc1905

commit_message:
Accept and emit union of keystone v2/v3 service

Keystone v3 changed the service_type field to type. Accept and emit
both, because programmers should not have to keep up with meaningless
trivia like that.

Change-Id: I56fc0191e1058e1d37cee9ee71d606624a0133a7

commit_message:
Add get_server_by_id optmization

There are times when you know you have a server id, so doing a
list/search/filter is inefficient. Provide a get_server_by_id
method so that in those situations you can bypass searching
server lists. Also, use the method in the other places.

Change-Id: I97bd52dff0854a3b4d41b5572e7490fa4df18e1e

commit_message:
Add auth hook for OpenStackClient

Since os_client_config started pulling in ksa plugins we have some
duplicate behaviour with OSC.  If o-c-c is going to be loading auth
plugins OSC needs a way to hook into the notch between setting config
values and actually loading the plugins in order to maintain existing
behaviours for compatibility.

It may also be desirable at some point to defer the plugin loading,
OSC did that orignally due to ksc's poor load times, ksa shouldn't
have the same problem.

Change-Id: I1e8a50e5467fd4f9151a64aa7ae140d2654f3186

Dirk: Lets have a proper discussion about openSUSE Leap support.'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-10-06 14:14:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

commit_message:
install: Liberty updates for obs (*suse/SLES)

* Updates relevant sections for openSUSE-*/SLES*
* Adds some work-arounds for potential deadends.
* Updates package and service names.

Change-Id: I85c1678d04737bc11915e3f3b1d9653abad1adaa
Implements: blueprint installguide-liberty

commit_message:
serial console: enhance help of options

The help of the options for the "serial console" feature didn't make
clear which service uses which option and which options depend on each
other. This patch set clarifies that.

Change-Id: I8f635435f8a09029da53eb81e7b4d33661630859

I realize you're debugging other stuff. Some notes from testing this 
patch locally in my 2-node DevStack env (on F22).

When this patch is applied to Nova git on Control node DevStack, which also runs `nova-compute` process, DevStack fails to build with this error. (NOTE: If I don't apply patch, DevStack builds successfully, noting here so that the issue seems to be isolated to the patch in  question.)

[. . .]
2015-06-26 09:00:27.203 | 2015-06-26 05:00:27.201 TRACE nova     changes = [self.version(v).script(database, op) for v in versions]
2015-06-26 09:00:27.203 | 2015-06-26 05:00:27.201 TRACE nova   File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/migrate/versioning/version.py", line 204, in script
2015-06-26 09:00:27.204 | 2015-06-26 05:00:27.201 TRACE nova     "There is no script for %d version" % self.version
2015-06-26 09:00:27.204 | 2015-06-26 05:00:27.201 TRACE nova AssertionError: There is no script for 294 version
[. . .]

However, if I apply this patch _only_ to Nova git on Compute node (rest is all plain DevStack from today's git.) DevStack builds successfully.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-06-29 09:45:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 11303, 'date': '2015-06-30 08:45:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Workflow

@Kashyap Chamarthy:

I used Devstack to double-check the issue you had and I couldn't
reproduce it. How did you apply the patch? I used Devstack's 
"local.conf" file like this:

    [[local|localrc]]
    # [...]
    NOVA_REPO=https://review.openstack.org/p/openstack/nova
    NOVA_BRANCH=refs/changes/58/188058/2

My Devstack version is:

    98b65249 2015-06-30 Merge "Tune mysql a bit better[...]

Since this change doesn't affect the versioning or DB migrate scripts,
I doubt that it is the cause for the error you described.

---

I put the workflow back to zero. My change didn't make anything worse.
As soon as someone enables the serial console, the libvirt tools command
"virsh console <domain>" won't work because it depends on a serial pty
and is not able to communicate with the serial tcp device. Since the 
serial tcp device (="serial console" feature) is the first one which 
gets defined it will be used as the first interactive console. This 
means, the serial pty device gets not cloned to an interactive console
device [1].

[1] http://libvirt.org/formatdomain.html#elementCharConsole'}, {'account_id': 6962, 'date': '2015-06-30 14:10:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

Err, it was PEBKAC. Dan Smith corrected me on IRC -- the error I was seeing was because of stale .pyc files in Nova. Doing this in Nova's `git` repo did it:

    $ rm -rf $(find . -name '*.pyc')

Just to answer your question, I applied the patch this way:

    # On Nova's master branch
    $ cd ../nova
    $ git fetch https://review.openstack.org/openstack/nova refs/changes/58/188058/2 && git checkout FETCH_HEAD"}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2015-07-15 12:48:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1
