Sorry, we cannot make this change - the idea is flawed in two critical ways & the blueprint should not have been approved.

There is a limit of 4 serial ports on x86, 1 is always present and the serial console feature allows users to request multiple consoles. So if there is an image property hw_serial_port_count=3, and we apply this change you propose the guest will have 5 consoles and will fail to boot with a QEMU error. IOW this proposal will cause a regression in behaviour from what was previously possible with nova means existing guests may well fail rebuild and existimg flavour/image settings may now fail to boot.

In addition for your suggested change to work all guest images will need to be altered. By default images are setup so that kernels will log boot up messages on the first serial port, but your change is adding the logfile as the last serial port, which means it will not actually receive any boot up messages. At the same time though admins may not wish to change the default port, because they want to use the default port from their serial console session.

The right way to deal with the problem of capturing early boot messages is for libvirt/QEMU to gain the ability to have a logging daemon which can record data from an existing serial console, rather than requiring yet another serial port to be added.'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2015-07-27 09:29:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

FYI i have been working on a libvirt virtlogd daemon to handle this scenario

http://www.redhat.com/archives/libvir-list/2015-January/msg00762.html'}, {'account_id': 11303, 'date': '2015-07-27 09:42:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Daniel Berrange:

Shouldn't the upper limit of 4 serial ports for x86 be checked in the code? Right now it is possible to set "hw_serial_port_count=5" and the boot should fail like you said.'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2015-07-27 09:45:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Yes, it will fail and should be checked'}, {'account_id': 11303, 'date': '2015-07-27 15:28:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I reported a bug which describes that the limit of 4 serial ports could be checked in Nova: https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1478607

I'll look for another solution which wouldn't introduce a regression. The pointer to the logging deamon locks promising."}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-08-04 11:40:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-2

Merge Failed.

This change or one of its cross-repo dependencies was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of its repository. Please rebase the change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 11303, 'date': '2015-09-15 12:05:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Daniel Berrange: 

You wrote: 

    "So if there is an image property hw_serial_port_count=3 [...]"

Bug 1425640 makes me believe that no one is using it this way right now. 
In short, the libvirt driver returns *always* and *only* the first 
created serial console device port, despite the number of created serial 
console devices. IOW, as a customer I'm able to create multiple devices 
but can only access the first one via the REST API... this doesn't seem 
to be useful to me.

You wrote: 

    "By default images are setup so that kernels will log boot up 
    messages on the first serial port, but your change is adding the 
    logfile as the last serial port"

Yes, that's true, I will change that.

You wrote:

    "At the same time though admins may not wish to change the 
    default port, because they want to use the default port from their
    serial console session."

I'm not quite sure if I get this right. Do you mean the port number
of the device within the guest (range: [0,1,2,3]), or the port number 
of the device which is exposed via the REST API (range: [10000..20000])? 
Because these to numbers are different, the REST API wouldn't be 
affected by this change, IIUC.

I also like to emphasize that, right now, the enablement of feature "A"
disables feature "B" (without warning or hints). And this is on a compute
node level! It is possible to rebuild an instance on a different compute
node which has the "serial console" feature enabled, and suddenly the 
REST API to get the console output [1] doesn't return anything. That's
an odd behavior and it doesn't feel right to me. 
I also  assume that the usage of the "serial console" feature with
the libvirt driver isn't that much spread, given that enabling that 
feature also breaks other things like "live-migration" (bug 1455252).

I really like to make this working again for the Liberty release. For
Mitaka we can attack the need for a "console.log" file by replacing it
with the virtlogd deamon, which would also solve bug 832507, IIUC.

[1] http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-compute-v2.1.html#os-console-output-v2.1'}, {'account_id': 11303, 'date': '2015-09-16 13:23:13.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-16 14:42:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

I think it is important to look at the conceptual architecture of the system at a higher level when trying to address this.

 - We have a REST API for getting logs from the primary VM console
 - We have a serial console feature which gives admins an interactive shell on the primary VM console (and ideally additional consoles)

Note, that we have two features both wanting the primary VM console. The current technical implementation doesn't allow for two clients to access the same console at once, but in the future we will have a virtlogd provided by libvirt which will expose the interactive console and be capable of logging data transmitted over it, so we can satisfy both features at once, which is our desired end goal.

In the absence of the ideal solution, there are three choices:

 - Don't support interactive serial console at all
 - Disable REST API access to console logs, if interactive serial console is enabled
 - Create multiple guest consoles, one of REST API, one for interactive usage

The initial implementation chose the second approach, of making use of these two features mutually exclusive. This is reasonable, because it means you do not need any changes to guest OS images and use of serial console is an opt-in.

Your proposal here is suggesting switching to the third approach, temporarily for mitaka. The problem with this is that a guest OS will only have one primary console, so if you two serial ports, you need to choose which one will be primary. Furthermore this likely requires guest OS image changes to be usable. Changes that would have to be reverted when Nova switched to the ideal solution later which only need a single  serial port for both logs & interactive usage.

While I admit the current log OR interactive console choice is not ideal, I believe it is better tradeoff than configuring multiple serial ports on the guest image."}, {'account_id': 11303, 'date': '2015-09-16 16:42:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

@Daniel Berrange: Thanks for your explanation and summary. Yes, I'd like to 
switch to the third approach, like you already mentioned. And to be 
honest, I still like to have this in Liberty. Because IIUC, 
right now, if an instances crashes during the boot and if the cloud admin has enabled the serial console feature on the host compute node, a user doesn't have any possibility to debug WHY this happended. Or do I miss 
something here?

A last possibility which comes to my mind to solve this until we have the "virtlogd" solution, is using the "kernel_args" in the flavor extra specs or
the image metadata:

    "console=ttyS1 console=ttyS0,115200"

By this, a user could opt-in by setting this on the flavor or image.
And as soon as the "virtlogd" solution is in place, the second console
arg in the kernel_args above would be silently ignored, because we would
only have one port which does both. It doesn't have to be removed that way. Maybe I'm thinking to naive here, you're feedback is highly welcomed.'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2015-09-17 08:24:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I really don't want us to do anything that implies changes to configuration of the image or guest OS, because this would either mean a regression when we do the desired real solution later, or impose an requirement to support this mode forever, neither of which are desirable IMHO."}, {'account_id': 11303, 'date': '2015-10-13 16:05:42.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Superseded by: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/libvirt-virtlogd'}]

commit_message:
libvirt: use log file and serial console at the same time

The config option "[serial_console].enabled" is used as a switch by
the libvirt driver to determine if EITHER the instance log file OR
the serial console should be created as a device for the guest.
Over the last months I was not able to get an answer why this design
was chosen. Frankly, I believe that it is a bug. Because I couldn't
find any "prove" that the current implementation is "wrong", I have
chosen the "blueprint way" to commit this change.

To be precise: If cloud admins set the compute node config option
"[serial_console].enabled" to "True", they prevent that the REST API
for the "os-getConsoleOutput" action for guests on these compute nodes
will return anything (because nothing gets logged). End users, who call
that REST API, will sometimes get a result and sometimes not, depending
on the configuration of the host where the instance gets scheduled to.

This patch set will allow the creation of BOTH devices (log file AND
serial console) for the guest. Which means that the REST API action
"os-getConsoleOutput" will return a result, even if the "serial console"
feature was enabled or not.

UpgradeImpact:
Instances, which get launched on compute nodes which have this patch,
will have 2 devices ("tcp" AND "file") instead of the 1 device
("tcp" OR "file") they get without this patch. Existing instances
which get migrated to a patched host, won't get the additional device
unless they get rebuild. Guests which were already built with multiple
serial devices (through flavor extra specs or image metadata) could
exceed the upper limit of 4 serial devices after a rebuild. Due to
bug 1425640, which says that the REST API only returns the very first
serial console device, I believe that this is not yet really exploited
by customers.

Implements: blueprint libvirt-log-file-and-serial-console

Change-Id: Ic6fbc2402daf28f4db4117be1c7ae7bc3d1a8e9b

commit_message:
Fix router port get tunnel_key method

tunnel_key is now part of the router port object, remove
the old methods used to store mapping between tunnel key and
the port name.
Fix the cookie id to take the tunnel id from the router port
object.

Closes-Bug: #1505616
Change-Id: Ice4657bd9fedab97b46c9eddb51d70c05eb4d76f

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-07-14 22:35:07.000000000', 'message': "Set RabbitMQ FD limit via rabbitmq-env.conf

The pacemaker RabbitMQ resource agent does not use systemd so we
can't resort to manage the FD via the puppet module (which sets
that in the unit limits.conf file); instead we paste it into
rabbitmq-env.conf, as per https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1240587

Closes-Bug: 1474586
Change-Id: I62d31e483641ccb5cf489df81146ecb31d0c423f
"}, {'created': '2015-07-14 22:58:01.000000000', 'message': "Parametrize RabbitMQ FD limit

Adds a parameter to configure RabbitMQ file limit; also note
the pacemaker RabbitMQ resource agent does not use systemd so we
can't resort to manage the FD via the puppet module only,
we paste it into rabbitmq-env.conf as well, more details can
be found at https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1240587

Closes-Bug: 1474586
Change-Id: I62d31e483641ccb5cf489df81146ecb31d0c423f
"}, {'created': '2015-07-16 12:37:58.000000000', 'message': "Parametrize RabbitMQ FD limit

Adds a parameter to configure RabbitMQ file limit; also note
the pacemaker RabbitMQ resource agent does not use systemd so we
can't resort to manage the FD via the puppet module only,
we paste it into rabbitmq-env.conf as well, more details can
be found at https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1240587

Closes-Bug: 1474586
Change-Id: I62d31e483641ccb5cf489df81146ecb31d0c423f

commit_message:
Parameterize RabbitMQ FD limit

Together with [1] this change permits to parameterize the file
descriptor limit for RabbitMQ for both the Systemd startup script
and the Pacemaker resource agent.

1. https://github.com/puppetlabs/puppetlabs-rabbitmq/commit/20325325b977c508b151ef8036107dcfefdf990b

Closes-Bug: 1474586
Change-Id: I62d31e483641ccb5cf489df81146ecb31d0c423f

commit_message:
Fix order of arguments in assertEqual

Some tests used incorrect order assertEqual(observed, expected).
The correct order expected by testtools is
assertEqual(expected, observed).

Change-Id: I72e1d8a6b52fa6dbb85b57438aef92ad13735880
Partial-Bug: #1259292

commit_message:
Change the type of some param into "xsd:list"

The type of following response parameters are actually "xsd:list":
  * "networks"
  * "subnets"
  * "ports"
  * "routers"
  * "floatingips"
  * "security_groups"
  * "security_group_rules"
  * "metering_labels"
  * "vips"
  * "health_monitors"
  * "members"
  * "subnetpools"

Nit bugfix:
  * "securityGroupParameter" -> "securityGroupsParameter"
  * "metering label"         -> "metering_label"
  * "metering label rule"    -> "metering_label_rule"

Change-Id: I74fcfa7b9e3c4cd04feb22191f95ae97ea3788b7
Closes-Bug: 1505040

Creating new SSH action which uses gateway

 * New SSH action uses gateway for accessing to guest network VMs

commit_message:
Fix assign_vip for default admin network case

Default fuelweb_admin doesn't belong to any node group, so we can't use
the same SQL query to this network. So let's fallback to default admin
network in case there's no admin network in conroller's node group.

Closes-Bug: #1484181

Change-Id: I93034d9555b0851cf9c3d525cd7118de5a089dc3
Signed-off-by: Igor Kalnitsky <igor@kalnitsky.org>

commit_message:
Remove dangling symlinks after node log removal

Dangling symlinks caused snapshots to generate without part of logs. The
symlinks were a leftover after deleteing logs from deleted nodes.

Existence of log folders was checked using os.path.exists function, it
was changed to os.path.lexists, which returns True for broken symlinks.

Change-Id: I446df0595ba668800e89f378ab08bd33cec4fb56
Closes-Bug: #1494838
(cherry picked from commit 2a327bd01e4e8570c28f10ce4a205b31868f5056)

commit_message:
Default ConvertedException code to 500

webob 1.5.0 released on 10/11 has change f6c749011 which
strictly enforces status codes in exceptions, and 0 is not
a valid status code so tests fail.

Change the default to 500 to match the default in the parent
class in webob.

Change-Id: If04eedb402092ca2cc307cb52f2231493c4375a2
Closes-Bug: #1505153
(cherry picked from commit 10438c0fc34bd088e018e1a5e8ec57b396528792)

[{'created': '2015-10-13 09:07:56.000000000', 'message': "Show exact error message when authentication falied instead of HTML body

When using pecan.abort() on server side, client side will see response
bodies for HTTP errors, which is not readable for end users.

This patch will let mistral client extract error message from header
returned by mistral serivce, currently, it's only used for
authentication failure.

Closes-Bug: #1502840

commit_message:
Show exact error message when authentication falied instead of HTML body

When using pecan.abort() on server side, client side will see response
bodies for HTTP errors, which is not readable for end users.

This patch will let mistral client extract error message from header
returned by mistral serivce, currently, it's only used for
authentication failure.

Closes-Bug: #1502840
Change-Id: I20a7f845676ffe23d93334d171332d717994d937
(cherry picked from commit a5e1e73e837e7f356b3a5c4f1fcfaef0d31aa5b8)

The instance_manager's current caching of instance_info only happens
once and is never refreshed.  This causes update_state() to not notice
a backing instance is gone until it fails a API liveliness check.

This fixes it by updating the instance_info on every run of ensure_cache(),

a booted instance that does not yet have ports associated.  This also
fixes this by considering instances with no management port to still
be in the booting state.

commit_message:
Properly detect backing instance is gone

The instance_manager's current caching of instance_info only happens
once and is never refreshed.  This causes update_state() to not notice
a backing instance is gone until it fails a API liveliness check.

This fixes it by updating the instance_info on every run of ensure_cache(),
in the same way it does for the router_obj.  This will properly detect
a backing instance is gone and rebuild the router without the slow
failing liveliness check.

Fixing this introduces a race where we try to check the API server of
a booted instance that does not yet have ports associated.  This also
fixes this by considering instances with no management port to still
be in the booting state.

Change-Id: I847b8a15239c7a195a0593ca50344ea7d5fe35c2
Closes-bug: #1492056

commit_message:
Delete VRRP and MGT ports on router delete

These ports are left behind when a router is deleted.
Stale VRRP ports prevent a tenant from deleting their own networks
as it is owned by the service VM but active and invisible to the tenant.
MGT ports dont block net delete but should be cleaned up regardless.

Closes-bug: #1491593

Change-Id: I8d93a7d4392e26dc1ca7940e31d47ddcb81b08ad

commit_message:
By default, add a secgroup rule to permit all private network traffic.

This is useful for debugging purposes.  It's often helpful to test
connectivity for tenant VMs via ICMP/TCP from within the router VM itself;  The
default demo tenant security group rules prevent this because they restrict
ingress traffic to the tenant's default security group (the router VM is on
a different tenant and has a different security group).

Change-Id: I20082154c9bacba15339d9d5883ba4bd10c542e7

commit_message:
Add small reminder to use latest vagrant

Vagrant is fast moving tech and we've seen some bugs around users using
old distro packaged versions
(https://bugs.launchpad.net/kolla/+bug/1505045).

Change-Id: I37ae4452fd95e8b58aec228d89bd98214ac012df
backport: liberty

commit_message:
Liberty release - openstackdocstheme 1.2.4

This release includes links for Liberty and is thus needed for the
upcoming release.
Besides that it fixes:
* Fix the broken anchor tags.
* Remove unused files.
* Fix table padding.

Change-Id: Idcca174e23c08936ee7abd79e65709681abf9372

commit_message:
Default ConvertedException code to 500

webob 1.5.0 released on 10/11 has change f6c749011 which
strictly enforces status codes in exceptions, and 0 is not
a valid status code so tests fail.

Change the default to 500 to match the default in the parent
class in webob.

Change-Id: If04eedb402092ca2cc307cb52f2231493c4375a2
Closes-Bug: #1505153

commit_message:
Add more components virtual ip mapping into controller.

Currently only Glance and Heat have their virtual IP passed to the
contrller directly.

This commit adds the same feature for :

 * Ceilometer
 * Cinder
 * Nova
 * Swift

Change-Id: I295d15d7a0aa33175a5530e3b155b0c61983b6ae

The message is just a warning and I don't think it's the reason why some configuration options have been lost.

Maintaining the neutron config-ref tables is becoming more and more painful and time consuming, the autohelp.py script must be updated at each run. I'm not sure that a simple solution exists though."}, {'account_id': 17207, 'date': '2015-09-16 09:38:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your suggestions
The problematic message is follows.

I saw this kind of error previously in cinder.'}, {'account_id': 7923, 'date': '2015-09-16 10:06:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Still not an error, but an information/warning. This doesn't prevent the script to run (just tested).

It's very probable that all the missing options have been moved to external repositories, which need to be added to https://github.com/openstack/openstack-doc-tools/tree/master/autogenerate_config_docs/requirements

I'm afraid I won't have to time to handle this, but I'm happy to help if someone wants to tackle this."}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-09-16 11:56:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I made a patch at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/224049/ which adds all the networking-* repos to the requirements file.

If someone could take that and test it, that would be appreciated!'}, {'account_id': 17207, 'date': '2015-09-16 13:36:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I tested it for  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/224049/
But the message is unchanged.

By the way, networking-lenovo seems different.
Not in openstack code repository.
So I use follows 
-e git+https://github.com/lenovo-network/networking-lenovo#egg=networking-lenovo'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-09-22 03:50:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

If the script isn't playing nice, perhaps a simpler way might be to ask the dev ML whether any of these drivers disappeared or something in this cycle:

    NEC OpenFlow
    SDNVE
    VMWare DVS
    l3_Arista
    ml2_arista
    ml2_cisco
    ml2_ncs
    plumgriddirector

?"}, {'account_id': 7923, 'date': '2015-09-29 16:21:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I still need to find time to validate this theory, but I'm guessing that external code (third party repos) is not imported anymore in the neutron code, so we should explicitely list repositories as additional python packages to parse, instead of just adding them as extra dependencies.

This is already done for {VPN,LB,FW}aaS, and should probably be done for other packages.

Again, I need to validate this assumption, but this might do the trick.

See https://github.com/openstack/openstack-doc-tools/blob/master/autogenerate_config_docs/autohelp-wrapper#L196-L202 and https://github.com/openstack/openstack-doc-tools/blob/master/autogenerate_config_docs/extra_repos/neutron-master"}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-10-08 06:37:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Update Config reference for neutron

  Edit section_network-plugins.xml
       section_network-plugins-ml2.xml
  Stay removed mlnx (mellanox)

  Unchanged because of trouble
       networking-ibm (SDN-VE)
       octavia

  Cannot include because of trouble
       networking-infoblox
       networking-zvm

  Consider neutron plugin addition (#1503967)

Change-Id: I41272af4ec46c7e7c1c3ce7d6e03c6a40fb0cb25
Partial-Bug: #1407581
Related-Bug: #1503967

commit_message:
Output format is corrected for wf-validate and wb-validate

Output of workflow-validate and workbook-validate was not
correct. Now output will be displayed in tabular format
by default. Output can be customized by user by giving
format option as described in doc.

Change-Id: Ic159f188236a99acbba2d3728a74da438b90e9b2
Closes-Bug: #1499626
(cherry picked from commit 19fd616b90188ba7c4f81362b5c13fdec68a0816)

The other option is to not do an exact conversion and assume the worst case upper bound on the number of bytes per character, which is 4. So take the length of the string and multiply by 4. That probably isn't a great answer in this case, as it could be overly conservative."}, {'account_id': 8126, 'date': '2015-10-07 20:16:37.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 8126, 'date': '2015-10-07 20:18:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Thanks for the review/comments Roland -- found a vertica page (see comment in java file) that indicates VJDBC uses UTF-16 -- so assuming 2 bytes per char.  Great catch!'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-07 20:26:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-monasca-api-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/87/231587/4/check/gate-monasca-api-pep8/a363c7f/ : SUCCESS in 57s
- gate-monasca-api-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/87/231587/4/check/gate-monasca-api-python27/8fed4a8/ : SUCCESS in 1m 22s
- gate-monasca-api-build http://logs.openstack.org/87/231587/4/check/gate-monasca-api-build/46d46ac/ : SUCCESS in 5m 09s'}, {'account_id': 8126, 'date': '2015-10-08 16:03:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Roland/All -- heard back from vertica support on this -- supporting our use of UTF-16:

It is safe if you check it from your application side, as per the link, below is the excerpts:

    JDBC applications use a UTF-16 character set encoding and are responsible for converting any non-UTF-16 encoded data to UTF-16. Failing to convert the data can result in errors or the data being stored incorrectly.


    The JDBC driver converts UTF-16 data to UTF-8 when passing to the HP Vertica server and converts data sent by HP Vertica server from UTF-8 to UTF-16 .

regards,
REDACTED
vertica Technical support

Are we OK to merge?'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-10-09 15:58:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Are these all true statements?

Java stores Strings as UTF16.
The Vertica JDBC serializes to UTF8, transmits as UTF8, and then deserializes to UTF16, and then stores as UTF16.
UTF16 is always 2 bytes per character, and never more. For example, UTF8 can use up to 4 characters to store, but this doesn't occur with UTF16.

If all the above are true statements, then I think we can merge."}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-10-09 16:09:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I just found this page at, http://unicode.org/faq/utf_bom.html,  which implies that UTF16 can be up to 4 bytes per character.

It doesn't look like a multiple of 2 is sufficient based on that page."}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-10-09 16:11:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Note, I used a multiplier of 4 in a recent change that I made in the Persister at, https://review.openstack.org/#/c/231741/.'}, {'account_id': 8126, 'date': '2015-10-09 16:34:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Roland,

This is definitely an area to be better safe than sorry -- i'll change to 4.

Thanks!
Brad"}, {'account_id': 8126, 'date': '2015-10-09 16:48:01.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-09 17:07:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-monasca-api-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/87/231587/5/check/gate-monasca-api-pep8/75e07f2/ : SUCCESS in 1m 02s
- gate-monasca-api-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/87/231587/5/check/gate-monasca-api-python27/08b76d2/ : SUCCESS in 1m 02s
- gate-monasca-api-build http://logs.openstack.org/87/231587/5/check/gate-monasca-api-build/d1b8b14/ : SUCCESS in 4m 00s'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-10-09 18:57:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

I wanted to really be done with this change. However, the Monasca API, https://github.com/stackforge/monasca-api/blob/master/docs/monasca-api-spec.md#post-v20metrics, says that the meta data is limited to 2048 characters. What is implemented now is restricting to 2048/4 characters. That is a pretty big difference. It is certainly conservative, and will fix the bug. The problem is that the Agent is expecting to to be able to send meta_value that is 2048 characters in length, and if it is actually testing for that size now, it is incorrect, and the API will want to reject a lot of values that are sent by the Agent.

I think the real fix is that the Vertica schema needs to be adjusted to VARCHAR(2048*4), and the API should just check for 2048. 

What do you think?'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-10-10 01:53:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

We could also make this configurable in the API. That is a simple change that satisfies everyone.

Maybe we should also implement a v2.0/limits endpoint where all these values could be returned to the client, and then we wouldn't have to have a hard-coded value in the API."}, {'account_id': 8126, 'date': '2015-10-12 22:05:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Roland -- all good ideas.  How about for now, we change the schema to varchar(8192) and then the api checks for a total length of all serialized json for the value_meta array to be 2048 or less?'}, {'account_id': 8126, 'date': '2015-10-12 22:11:36.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-12 22:11:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change or one of its cross-repo dependencies was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of its repository. Please rebase the change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 8126, 'date': '2015-10-13 14:47:17.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

having rebase issues, change now at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/234266/'}]

commit_message:
Scope requests to horizon scoped region

Instead of adding region to all requests by default if not
specified, we'll instead honor a region of 'inject_scoped_region'.
This is because not all environments add region as a dimension
for metrics, so we can't do this by default.

Change-Id: Id2d2e5f4d80d14e37d10890d351a919302ece7ec
Closes-Bug: #1494337

commit_message:
py3: Run unit tests with ostestr on Python 3.4

"tox -e py34" now uses ostestr instead of testtools.run to run tests.
Tests are now executed in parallel.

Move the tests whitelist from tox.ini to a new file tests-py3.txt.

Fix NaElement.__str__() of netapp driver: return Unicode on Python 3,
not bytes.

Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: I4cda85fbe76ac853beaec3a9587726166daa063d

commit_message:
vmware: use cache_prefix to preserve cache directory

Currently value of `my_ip' config option is used as image cache dir
prefix to prevent races between nova-compute instances using the same
datastore.

The common practice of making nova-compute (with vmwareapi driver
chosen) HA is to have it run in active/passive mode controlled by
Pacemaker.  In that case Pacemaker can move nova-compute instance to
another host, should something happen to the original one, which
effectively will cause change of the IP address - thus, all cached
images will have to be re-downloaded again, despite the fact they are
still there in the datastore and still belong to this particular
nova-compute instance.

I02e758af19cf3a652a5c39d02904e73a1088fe60 made it possible to use the
`cache_prefix' config option to denote, which cache directory should
be used by a particular nova-compute instance. As long as we set the
same `cache_prefix' value for all nova-compute processes running in
active/passive mode, the cache directory will be the same on every
host.

Closes-Bug: #1482121

(cherry-picked from 7f064e855378e3ade9988170af506b2dd180f32e)
Change-Id: Id70dd29a757f41c9d02a3573c6581ba29e63b191

commit_message:
Install python-virtualenv for upgrade script

Since we are going to completely re-factor upgrade scripts approach,
we need to have simple workaround without publishing
python-virtualenv scripts in our updates mirror

Change-Id: I14a5f78b323c1c62a9986b3536ba7dde79ec5fb3
Closes-bug: #1505210

commit_message:
keystoneclient 1.8.0

We need a release of keystoneclient for M so that we can stop requests 2.8.0
from being used since it breaks everything.

The last release of keystoneclient was 1.7.1 which is for L so upping the
minor release #.

 777588a Updated from global requirements

Change-Id: Ie56170eff972977b58070b0a2b83518912c0ad15
Partial-Bug: 1505326

commit_message:
keystonemiddleware 2.4.0

We need a release of keystonemiddleware for M so that we can stop
requests 2.8.0 from being used since it breaks everything.

The last release of keystonemiddleware was 2.3.0 which is for L so
upping the minor release #.

Change-Id: I01e7c479afa982ef33e0055513ee2bdbf7924261
Closes-Bug: 1505326

commit_message:
Skip offline nodes in post deployment hooks

UploadNodesInfo and UpdateHosts hooks are not run on offline nodes,
which causes the deployment to not set all nodes in error state after
successful deployment.

Information about offline nodes is however carried on to newly deployed
nodes, as they can only be offline temporarily.

Change-Id: Ie33645bf755c7227e10b755118ed539641c5b624
Closes-bug: #1502295

commit_message:
Add support of CentOS7/RedHat7 to l23network

* Add CentOS6 and CentOS7 separation to l23_os fact.
* Use l23_os fact instead of osfamily.
* Add CentOS7/RedHat7 support to l23_stored_config resource.
* Remove *vconfig* package due to we do not use *vconfig* to configure vlan
 interfaces hence we do not need to install it. CentOS7/RedHat7 does not have this
 package anymore as well.

Change-Id: Ia6cb9e4efc9465030fe0ed8c2e46922db1513a74
Closes-bug: #1503157

commit_message:
Change default network provider to Neutron

In previous release (Fuel 7.0) nova-network is became deprecated, and
that means it will be dropped in Fuel 8.0. So let's change default to
neutron, because IIUC nova-network is already removed from
fuel-library's master and some swarm tests are broken.

Closes-Bug: #1503657
Closes-Bug: #1505258

Change-Id: I65a0ca2906503cb9c83fd99fddda9a8ee5156b16

commit_message:
Add testresources and testscenarios used by oslo.db fixture

If we use oslo.db fixtures, we'll need these 2 packages or
the next version of oslo.db release will break us.

Change-Id: I7c0d2f6dabc20bd4ff0d29d3b47b948aa24ea56b
Closes-Bug: #1503501

commit_message:
Default ConvertedException code to 500

webob 1.5.0 released on 10/11 has change f6c749011 which
strictly enforces status codes in exceptions, and 0 is not
a valid status code so tests fail.

Change the default to 500 to match the default in the parent
class in webob.

Closes-Bug: #1505153
(cherry picked from commit 10438c0fc34bd088e018e1a5e8ec57b396528792)

Change-Id: I16f91ff68380dd3bd47ae53462f289e9f4af5d49

commit_message:
Put all the logging related parameters to the logging class

Currently logging configuration is splitted in two distinct classes,
the init.pp and the logging.pp classes. This review aims to centralize
all logging related parameters in a single class, the logging.pp one.

The impacted parameters are :

  * use_syslog
  * use_stderr
  * log_facility
  * verbose
  * debug
  * log_dir

This change remains backward compatible with what is currently in place.

Change-Id: Ibb75be575420d49f99c9841b957e2b12cdedea41

I'm really torn on this.  We definitely expected ssync to be able to work this way - and acoles patch is super straight forward.  But ultimately the "feature" that prevents a remote node from syncing a fragment index onto a node until it hands off the other fragment index that doesn't belong here might not be such a bad thing.  The big problem might have more to do with how it effects other fragments in the partition - so maybe fixing it for now is the best thing - while still recognizing we may not want to encourage the reconstructor to overload a particular device with more than one fragment because it could really effect the availability story.

Probably need to discuss in Vancouver.

But for now I'm working on a probetest to help us understand the situation when the reconstructor would *want* to put more than one fragment index on the same node and decide if there's a failure mode that's actually scary enough we should try to push something like this into RC2?'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2015-04-20 08:37:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-17 13:47:18.000000000', 'message': 'Allow multiple fragments to be PUT at same timestamp

Make the object server accept a PUT at same timestamp as
existing object if the PUT has a different fragment index
than existing object. This is necessary to allow the
reconstructor to revert/rebuild an EC fragment to a
node that might already have a handoff fragment.

Also, make ssync_receiver robust to receiving HTTP_CONFLICT or
HTTP_NOT_FOUND responses from the object server, in case it does
attempt to PUT the same fragment index at same timestamp or
DELETE an object after it has been deleted. These are not errors.

Update tests to verify these cases.

Change-Id: Iee438e5667c3a673ab3e07c45e7c96cb11b646a0
'}]
commit_message:
Allow multiple fragments to be PUT at same timestamp

Make the object server accept a PUT at same timestamp as
existing object if the PUT has a different fragment index
than existing object. This is necessary to allow the
reconstructor to revert/rebuild an EC fragment to a
node that might already have a handoff fragment.

Also, make ssync_receiver robust to receiving HTTP_CONFLICT or
HTTP_NOT_FOUND responses from the object server, in case it does
attempt to PUT the same fragment index at same timestamp or
DELETE an object after it has been deleted. These are not errors.

Update tests to verify these cases.

Change-Id: Iee438e5667c3a673ab3e07c45e7c96cb11b646a0

commit_message:
Lower retries of playbook runs to 2 as default value.

This will allow operators to earlier intervene in situations where manual corrections are necessary.

Closes-Bug: 1496870

commit_message:
Enable ARP spoofing protection for Neutron

ARP Spoofing protection in Neutron should be enabled be default

Upstream patch: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/225131
Patch for Neutron module: https://review.fuel-infra.org/#/c/11865/
Closes-bug: #1496336

Change-Id: If7b25f0618f40040714b6e54c1498dd959c2a610

commit_message:
Remove unused 'deprecated' option from auth_strategy opt

auth_strategy option in cinder/common/config.py has a
'deprecated' option. I can only see that 'no_auth' and
'keystone' are used anywhere in the code. Looking at
the git logs it appears that the 'deprecated' option
may have been pulled over when we split from Nova.
This patch removes the unused option.

Closes-Bug: #1504713
Change-Id: I40a67710d0e4c213ef6a1649b65b0480d63ee077

Fix 409 response when updating an image by removing read-only property

Added check "validate_change" for request PATCH operation "remove".

Change-Id: I0c268e1d44a48c0f0f66856e7a87205c846c70e3
Closes-bug: #1443563

commit_message:
Encode Location header in utf-8

We get Location header in unicode format. Need to encode it to utf-8
format, otherwise heat won't work on some requests running via
mod_wsgi.

Closes-Bug: #1500807
Change-Id: I8950360e71cd62baf899d0aff822b981b5d99068

[{'created': '2015-07-06 18:16:00.000000000', 'message': 'Overload Fixture._setUp instead of Fixture.setUp

Since fixtures==1.3.0, we should overload Fixture._setUp instead of
Fixture.setUp as Fixture base class can detect failures during _setUp
and trigger any registered cleanups. It avoids resource leakage when
(_)setUp fails.

Change-Id: Ief9d4fefc4ae0a8b4caa0493b352321bb2f07e2a
'}]
commit_message:
Overload Fixture._setUp instead of Fixture.setUp

Since fixtures==1.3.0, we should overload Fixture._setUp instead of
Fixture.setUp as Fixture base class can detect failures during _setUp
and trigger any registered cleanups. It avoids resource leakage when
(_)setUp fails.

Change-Id: Ief9d4fefc4ae0a8b4caa0493b352321bb2f07e2a

commit_message:
Locked dependency versions

NPM, by default, uses fuzzy version matching to resolve dependencies.
This can cause some volatility in the build, especially if transient
dependencies change. Locking down these versions gets us closer
to a repeatable build.

Change-Id: I053e7e5b75b8a46dd17a99ebfa559bade0d2f3e5

webob.exc.WSGIHTTPException() constructor now fails with a KeyError
when the HTTP status code is 0.

test_exceptions_raise() of test_misc tries to instanciate all

fix the unit test. The bug is only in the test,
cinder/api/openstack/wsgi.py copies an existing HTTP code:

    Fault(exception.ConvertedException(code=ex_value.code,  ...)

'}]
commit_message:
Fix test_misc for WebOb 1.5

WebOb 1.5 was released at 2015-10-11. With this new version,
webob.exc.WSGIHTTPException() constructor now fails with a KeyError
when the HTTP status code is 0.

test_exceptions_raise() of test_misc tries to instanciate all
exceptions of cinder.exception. The problem is that
ConvertedException uses a default HTTP status code of 0.

Modify the default HTTP status code of ConvertedException to 400 to
fix the unit test. The bug is only in the test,
cinder/api/openstack/wsgi.py copies an existing HTTP code:

    Fault(exception.ConvertedException(code=ex_value.code,  ...)

Closes-Bug: #1505153
Change-Id: I1aec8038774828d48da4b0e831b390e33243809a
(cherry picked from commit 867fccf833ffc597aa986cb6ff1b3b5c1101b9ba)

commit_message:
Fix Kuryr check the length of networks and subnets correctly

This patch fixes Kuryr check the length of the resources in the
response from Neutron appropriately, which is the dictionary with the
key, the pluralised resource name.

Change-Id: I59e91887543fba4f2b4d5a38b28af65b3781febb
Signed-off-by: Taku Fukushima <f.tac.mac@gmail.com>
Closes-Bug: #1503517

commit_message:
Fix order of argument in assertEqual

Some tests used incorrect argument order in
assertEqual(observed, expected).

The correct order expected by testtools is
assertEqual(expected, observed)

Partial-Bug: #1259292

    if self.minimum is not None and value < self.minimum:

commit_message:
py3: MultiType.validate() now catchs TypeError

On Python 3, calling wtypes.validate_value() can fail with TypeError.
Example of error:

  File "solum/api/controllers/v1/datamodel/types.py", line 109, in validate
    return wtypes.validate_value(t, value)
  File ".../site-packages/wsme/types.py", line 370, in validate_value
    return datatype.validate(value)
  File ".../site-packages/wsme/types.py", line 166, in validate
    if self.minimum is not None and value < self.minimum:
  TypeError: unorderable types: list() < int()

Partially implements: blueprint solum-python3
Change-Id: I5eb0ac74d4c0df47a87d2fb8374b680b89ebd45c

commit_message:
py3: Replace types.BooleanType with bool

This change makes modified code compatible with Python 3.

Replace six.types.BooleanType with bool and six.types.FloatType with
float. types.BooleanType and types.FloatType were removed on
Python 3, but bool and float types are available on Python 2 and
Python 3.

By the way, six.types is simply the types module. No need to
get it from the six module.

Partially implements: blueprint solum-python3
Change-Id: I94498ee074eb5256bd4b291b802a836daceab74c

commit_message:
py3: Get httplib and __builtin__ from six.moves

* Replace httplib with six.moves.http_client
* Replace __builtin__ with six.moves.builtins

These two modules were renamed in Python 3 (to http.client and
builtins). Use six.moves to have code working on Python 2 and
Python 3.

Partially implements: blueprint solum-python3
Change-Id: Ic8d150697e3aec83403c3219d23548f5e598803c

commit_message:
py3: Replace dict.iteritems() with dict.items()

* Replace dict.iteritems() with dict.items()
* Replace six.iteritems(dict) with dict.items()
* Replace set(six.iterkeys(dict)) with set(dict)

On Python 2, there is a little overhead to create a temporary list,
but it was decided that it is negligible:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/066391.html

Partially implements: blueprint solum-python3
Change-Id: I5060f3a642a1ec95a6dc995577beff521f86ee11

* Replace string.lowercase with string.ascii_lowercase

string.letters was removed on Python 3, whereas string.ascii_letters
is available on Python 2 and Python 3.

By the way, string.letters is modified when the LC_CTYPE locale is
modified by locale.setlocale(). Hopefuly, Solum doesn't call

commit_message:
Replace string.letters with string.ascii_letters

* Replace string.letters with string.ascii_letters
* Replace string.lowercase with string.ascii_lowercase

string.letters was removed on Python 3, whereas string.ascii_letters
is available on Python 2 and Python 3.

By the way, string.letters is modified when the LC_CTYPE locale is
modified by locale.setlocale(). Hopefuly, Solum doesn't call
locale.setlocale().

Partially implements: blueprint solum-python3
Change-Id: I931e168fbb16679e79dd127b002a1538603fb0d5

commit_message:
Fix sshutils for error in writing received data

The data received from ssh destination is almost bytes class.
We should convert the data into string in order to write stdout or stderr.

Change-Id: I57555d6f54c3c1659806725001010a7eaf6ca96f
Closes-Bug: #1505051

commit_message:
Improve DVR scale performance

Only process floating ips on a router that are relevant to the agent
hosting the router (don't process floating ips assigned to a router
if the associated vm is not hosted on the compute node requesting the
router sync). In this way, the number of database calls made during
the DVR router updates is optimized to eliminate unnecessary
duplication of calls which return the same data or are made to get
data for routers which are not relevant to the sync_routers request
from the agent.

Partial-Bug: #1413314

Conflicts:
	neutron/db/l3_dvr_db.py
	neutron/db/l3_dvrscheduler_db.py

Change-Id: I4e8477bb61ffff164d2f3bbebb94e95a25838ce0
(cherry picked from commit b96a22661290ce2ea747537512eab2fb767679e6)

commit_message:
Fix the order of iterations in DB

Results are collected in the order of the finishing instead of order
of starting iteration.

To fix this we can just sort results by their timestampts.

This can be done in case of chunks as well so it won't block
work on distributed load generation

Change-Id: Ie8635d04aa7a2dd2a8ba9283a555140873000758
Closes-bug: #1492583

(1 comment)

oslo.log 1.12 release broke Gnocchi, this change should fix Gnocchi support:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-October/076810.html

(Julien wrote a different change but it's basically the same thing than Dims's patch: make pyinotify optional.)

About the API change (FastWatchedFileHandler and EventletThreadedNotifier classes moved to a new submodule): can someone please run a "full OpenStack" grep to ensure that these classes are not used outside oslo.log please?

Julien's change makes pyinotify optional without breaking the API.

IMHO we took a bad habit of making too many symbols public in Oslo which makes me feel bad each time that a symbol is moved or even removed.

I would prefer a more blackbox API. For example, FastWatchedFileHandler and EventletThreadedNotifier may be private and see as an implementation detail. oslo.log should pick the best handler according to user configuration.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-10-13 07:44:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
symbol and command modifications on Galera in HA guide

mysql> GRANT SELECT ON `mysql`.`user` TO ‘debian-sys-maint’@’localhost'
IDENTIFIED BY '<debian.cnf password>';
Symbols like ` should be changed to '

cp debian.cnf debian.cnf.old
would be better for beginners if replaced by:
cp /etc/mysql/debian.cnf /etc/mysql/debian.cnf.old.

Change-Id: I5dcdc2b617ab5bf900f66b2776c557d5336d392b
Closes-bug: #1497260

commit_message:
Remove 'not_analyzed' from server.name

Remove 'not_analyzed' from server name. In general,
not_analyzed should only be used for id fields and those where it
doesn't make sense to tokenize values.

Change-Id: I35bff3a422d1a809b461e3f1fdf162e2fb1c5f24
Closes-Bug: #1505358

commit_message:
Fix functional test_server tests

Now oslo.service 0.10.0 no longer sends SIGHUP to parent and
children services.

This was a chance introduced by 286a6ea, and since it invalidated
the very logic under test, this must be revised.

Change-Id: I18a11283925369bc918002477774f196010a1bc3
Closes-bug: #1505438

commit_message:
The docs say to run "su -s /bin/sh -c "keystone-manage db_sync" keystone"
however there is no output, if you omit the su -s it returns the correct
output and commands run correctly(verified by running the updated command.
Closes-Bug: #1505466

Change-Id: I0ddafc937f79731a980a4b5d2e8e24ab5e47c65b

commit_message:
Preserve usage and reservations on quota deletion

Current API deletes quota usage and reservations on quota limit
deletion.

According to API documentation what should only happen is that quotas
limits revert to default values by deleting tenant/user limits.

This patch fixes this issue.

APIImpact: Delete on os-quota-sets will no longer remove usage and
           reservation quotas. Those quotas are handled by Cinder
           service.
UpgradeImpact: There is no upgrade impact afaik.
Closes-Bug: #1410034
Change-Id: I9340b6f78623cfa5b505886ad75b8e4d3cd6131b
(cherry picked from commit 0ee1ea83b90de8d342fa242e311f1680fef66a92)

as cinder have mark-host-down API implemented in Liberty.

commit_message:
Workaround test stream corruption issue

We don't see it right now in logstash as we fail with
a Segmentation fault (core dumped) because of other
issues. But will end up seeing it once that is fixed.

Closes-Bug: #1492505
Change-Id: I6507e693fc929e03884f933bbda241f744d3a7c0

[{'created': '2015-10-07 06:09:53.000000000', 'message': 'Modify KuryrException extend Exception appropriately

commit_message:
Modify KuryrException extend Exception appropriately

This patch modifies KuryrException call the initializer of the super
class. This fixes Kuryr not to return the empty error response.

Change-Id: I728a24df6f20a81090c98aac46be22f3d27cd884
Signed-off-by: Taku Fukushima <f.tac.mac@gmail.com>
Closes-Bug: #1503518

commit_message:
Remove external service/package reference

W/o this patch, the neutron's plugins and agents
classes cannot be used in separate catalog runs from
the main neutron/neutron-server classes.

This is an issue for the components decoupling.

The solution is to use collectors for external
service/package references.

Partial-bug: #1489897
Related blueprint atomic-classes-orchestration
Change-Id: Ibccf91575361445c8654440182615de90af81099
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Remove external class Neutron reference

W/o this patch, the neutron, neutron-server, its plugins
and agents classes cannot be used in separate catalog runs.

This is an issue for the components decoupling.

The solution is to remove external class references
and delegate these to the composition layer, which is
out of the scope of the neutron PO module.

Partial-bug: #1489897
Related blueprint atomic-classes-orchestration
Change-Id: Ic569c7eecf2d8b777c729340858dd103c2e7bfcd
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Drop unused obj_to_primitive() override

This was a band-aid override until o.vo gained the obj_relationships fix
that this method overrides. That has been in place since o.vo 0.8.0, which
means this is long since no longer necessary (and is actually blocking our
ability to absorb bug fixes to this code in o.vo). Further, we no longer
use this directly because we're doing backports based on version manifests,
which means we no longer consult child_versions _or_ obj_relationships.

Change-Id: Id0ffd492afcbce596b0478fbcacca8bd05736929

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html

commit_message:
Add the mising requriements.

oslo.log and oslo.serialization need to be added into
requirements.txt or openstack client may not find the modules when
it tries to get the plugin mudules.

Change-Id: I9649c1fba9c54a256a79f3f959a0cc1d7e56311f
Closes-Bug: #1505479

commit_message:
Add state info to tasks list

When publish fails for a task, the error message will be recorded in
state info. This patch refactors the task list command to include the
state info.

Change-Id: I4a02fb34d7a1f2be3f0a64a808670a35a198f139
Closes-Bug: #1496685
(cherry picked from commit a87923d92f4fd05bcc75c36d8970789dd8005630)

commit_message:
Remove disable_service from DBs configuration

Remove disable_service from configure_for_func_testing.
A recent Devstack patch (Linked in bug report) checks
that a disabled service is not enabled later. This breaks
the code this patch touches. I believe the DBs were disabled
and enabled with the assumption that Devstack expects only
a single DB to be configured at a time, but that doesn't
seem to be the case. Simply removing the disable calls seems
to work fine.

Also exclude oslo.messaging==2.6.0 as per global-requirements.txt.

Closes-Bug: #1505259
Closes-Bug: #1505295

Depends-On: I47ab12f719fba41c2f0c03047b05eb28f4423682
Change-Id: I0fbcc1218e1aa9adbf89f6121c1c2e224ed93cab

commit_message:
py3: Replace basestring with six.string_types

The builtin basestring type was removed in Python 3. Replace it with
six.string_types which works on Python 2 and Python 3.

Change-Id: Ib92a729682322cc65b41050ae169167be2899e2c

commit_message:
Replace itertools.ifilter with six.moves.filter

Replace itertools.ifilter() with six.moves.filter(). The
itertools.ifilter was removed in Python 3. This change makes modified
code compatible with Python 2 and Python 3.

Replace itertools.izip() with six.moves.zip().

The patch was generated by the itertools operation of the sixer tool.

Change-Id: Ie7f787cc6d66edfceb8fa2c1a906351a8c8c5fed

Tempest's requirements on master will never be able to match with the requirements on stable branches. Tempest only has a master branch, there are no stable branches on tempest. So we only keep tempest master in sync with master g-r.

Even if you were to backport the tempest-lib bump there is no guarantee that any of the other requirements match from master tempest are in sync with what we have in global requirements on a stable branch. Keeping tempest in sync with with global requirements on master is mutually exclusive from being co-installable with a project's stable branches. It's like asking to install stable/juno neutron on the same node as master nova. 

This is why for gate runs (and any stable devstack deployment) we isolate the tempest install in a virtualenv to make sure the requirements don't interfere with each other. If you need to co-install tempest on the same box as a stable branch deployment (which I never recommend since there is no reason to do this as tempest is essentially an api client) you have to use a venv to install tempest."}, {'account_id': 7069, 'date': '2015-10-13 04:27:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 6133, 'date': '2015-10-13 07:16:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-13 07:16:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

commit_message:
Bump minimum tempest-lib version

Now we(Tempest team) are migrating common part of Tempest to tempest-lib
for running Tempest-like test on each project repository.
That work requires the latest tempest-lib. So this patch bumps minimum
tempest-lib version.

Change-Id: I9e6c6d2fd1e83247bc170d1cbdaa91593919d14b

commit_message:
Improving GlanceStoreException

This code improves current implementation of base
store exception with several things:
1. default message shouldn't be an empty string
and has to provide some information.
2. __init__ has to accept position parameter with
message string to bring glance_store to conformity
with glance.
3. 'super' should use GlanceStoreException instead of
just Exception.

Note: This matches the behaviour of glance_store's exceptions
with glance's.

Co-authored-by: Mike Fedosin <mfedosin@mirantis.com>
Co-authored-by: Stuart McLaren <stuart.​mclaren@hp.​com>

Closes-bug: 1501443

Change-Id: I04d25874de1c0ec0c46d094c4d9144412e0ae5c9
(cherry picked from commit 845254f5e17d159964249bc8d8cb2c84bf110e92)

Any gate work will have to happen in OpenStack infra unless someone wants to take on setting up an external CI. For now breaking out the upgrade process is the best way to ensure a deployer has the ability to recover from failure or run things individually. With the way that current RPC Juno > OpenStack-Ansible Kilo upgrades currently work its nearly impossible to recover from failure without intimate knowledge of the systems and how they're supposed to work especially if the failure happens in the script processes of the upgrade.

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-16 14:55:13.000000000', 'message': 'Break apart and document the upgrade process

This change breaks up the Juno>Kilo upgrade script such that its now
available to be called as separate pieces. This change allows the
deployer to call the various parts of the upgrade script as needed.
Special care has been taken to make the BASH parts of the script as
idempotent as possible

Documentation has been added to cover all of the scripts, what they
do, how they do it, and when to call them. While the `run-upgrade.sh`
script is the main entry point to doing an online upgrade, the script
itself is now simply an orchestrator which can be followed or
customized as needed.

The documentation should cover most, if not all, of the aspects of
an RPC Juno > OpenStack-Ansible Kilo upgrade. The deployer will
also have information on what we consider best practice and should
have the information required to make a decision on realistic
deliverables while migrating an old deployment to the new community
format which includes upgrading the installed OpenStack release as
well.

Change-Id: I82c347c1a5f911a95e58f502bb67bf10b2005b15

commit_message:
Break apart and document the upgrade process

This change breaks up the Juno>Kilo upgrade script such that its now
available to be called as separate pieces. This change allows the
deployer to call the various parts of the upgrade script as needed.
Special care has been taken to make the BASH parts of the script as
idempotent as possible

Documentation has been added to cover all of the scripts, what they
do, how they do it, and when to call them. While the `run-upgrade.sh`
script is the main entry point to doing an online upgrade, the script
itself is now simply an orchestrator which can be followed or
customized as needed.

The documentation should cover most, if not all, of the aspects of
an RPC Juno > OpenStack-Ansible Kilo upgrade. The deployer will
also have information on what we consider best practice and should
have the information required to make a decision on realistic
deliverables while migrating an old deployment to the new community
format which includes upgrading the installed OpenStack release as
well.

A play was added `swift-repo-adjustments.yml` to verify all hosts
have access to the ubuntu backports repositories as they're
required both in and outside of a container.

A restart was added to the swift rsyncd service restart handler
because the rsyncd service configs have shifted around and in some
cases its necessary for the service to be stopped and started more
than once to clean up old pid files.

Change-Id: I82c347c1a5f911a95e58f502bb67bf10b2005b15
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Fix obsolete imports in functional tests

isolated_creds was renamed to dynamic_creds in murano functional
tests. Also, update class names.

Change-Id: I3596a80925dde388dcb69a37ee4fd0343849b352
Closes-Bug: #1504508

commit_message:
Fix return value of reserve_fixed_ip client method

In Fixed ip service client, reserve_fixed_ip method does not
return the response body.

As per consistency in service client interfaces, this method should
return the response value even that is empty body.

This commit makes reserve_fixed_ip method to return the resp body.
Also implement unit tests for the same.

After changes are merged in tempest these needs to be sync in lib.

partially implements: blueprint method-return-value-and-move-service-clients-to-lib

Change-Id: I2cb1ef8dacd1994576656cfb108dd2eef2fbd988

commit_message:
Default auth_url is set, if it is not provided.

If auth_url is not provided by user error message
is displayed in html format.
Default auth_url is set in case it is not
provided.

I don't claim anything. For me, Python 3 is *not* supported.

commit_message:
Fix Python 3 issues in tests

* get StringIO from six.StringIO to support Python 2 and Python 3
* Replace "__builtin__.open" with "six.moves.builtins.open" to mock
  open()
* Workaround a Python 3.4.0 regression: get the log level directly
  from logging._nameToLevel instead of using logging.getLevelName().

Replace Python 3.3 with Python 3.4:

* tox.ini: replace py33 test environment with py34
* setup.cfg: replace "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.3"
  classifier with "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.4"

Change-Id: Ied495f5867f47eee57b64ab35c0423913ee17d6e

commit_message:
Add testresources and testscenarios used by oslo.db fixture

If we use oslo.db fixtures, we'll need these 2 packages or
the next version of oslo.db release will break us.

Closes-Bug: #1503501
Change-Id: I8facdaf69c79b1b1ae4f9f64e9856e12f14440ed

commit_message:
add python-tox into dev-quickstart doc

There is no python-tox in the list of ubuntu prerequisites,
so can not run tox command. With this patch, will add it.

And for fedora/redhat/centos systems, maybe there is same issue,
will address with other patches once get these systems env ready.

Change-Id: I239523520ea5580ce3a8023f4aea7f67b9362888
Closes-bug:#1505523

commit_message:
Fix requirements for Windows

There isn't pyinotify library available on Windows, so this library
must be install conditionaly.

Change-Id: I65ec441ea9c34671e8172f956a9c0a200d13aa5e

commit_message:
Block oslo.messaging 2.6.0 and webob 1.5.0

There is an AttributeError in oslo.messaging 2.6.0 which breaks
nova unit tests if zmq is not loaded.

There is also a bug in unit tests with webob 1.5.0.

The two fixes are co-dependent on requirements caps so we can move
forward.

There are two dependencies:

1. Mirror the g-r fix for oslo.messaging.
2. Depend on the global-requirements change for webob.

Partial-Bug: #1505295
Partial-Bug: #1505153

Co-Authored-By: Matt Riedemann <mriedem@us.ibm.com>

Change-Id: I45189bb8d31819e55e2955b22aa1146257578d14

If one program opens file(in our case log file) and this file is moved
or removed by other program, the first program still works with opened
file descriptor.
If we use WatchedFileHandler it allows to recreate file only after
first emitting of WatchedFileHandler. It means that deleted files still
consumes disk space.
Class FastWatchedFileHandler is designed to observe file system. If log
file is moved or removed FastWatchedFileHandler instantaneously closes
old file descriptor and creates new file with specified name.

commit_message:
FastWatchedFileHandler class was added

If one program opens file(in our case log file) and this file is moved
or removed by other program, the first program still works with opened
file descriptor.
If we use WatchedFileHandler it allows to recreate file only after
first emitting of WatchedFileHandler. It means that deleted files still
consumes disk space.
Class FastWatchedFileHandler is designed to observe file system. If log
file is moved or removed FastWatchedFileHandler instantaneously closes
old file descriptor and creates new file with specified name.
Config option watch-log-file was added. If this option is set
FastWatchedFileHandler handler will be used.
Option watch-log-file brings effect for Linux platform only.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1437444
Change-Id: Ie70c70ad2d8cf198a8fd72488a43fb1bd71c57be

[{'created': '2013-12-06 14:04:33.000000000', 'message': 'Implement basic functionalities for port forwarding

This commit implements a new L3 extension which integrated a new data
field "portforwardings" into L3 router. L3 agent can use this information
to insert iptables rules for port forwarding into corresponding router's
iptables.

This commit only implements very basic features. Features like 1) determine
outside address automatically; 2) check if inside address exists will be
implement in subsequent patches

Implement blueprint router-port-forwarding

commit_message:
Implement basic functionalities for port forwarding

This commit implements a new L3 extension which integrated a new data
field "portforwardings" into L3 router. L3 agent can use this information
to insert iptables rules for port forwarding into corresponding router's
iptables.

Implement blueprint router-port-forwarding

Change-Id: I4355c7148d74692d2a7945f8b25efd26a90415c4

commit_message:
[Ironic] Set openstack-contoller parameters for ironic

Ironic requires custom parameters scheduler_host_manager class
in '::nova::scheduler::filter' to get proper scheduling of
baremetal instances.

Partially Implemets: blueprint fuel-integrate-ironic

Change-Id: I49365a57ab55ed7fd2935f2e89025b038f321ab0

commit_message:
Add tftp module

 * This change pulls puppetlabd-tftp (0.2.3) via
   lirarian-puppet
 * This module is needed for ironic to provide
   bootstrapping mechanizm

Partially Implements: blueprint fuel-integrate-ironic
Change-Id: Icf7dcf7605959797a41cf8c08964a311279ffb83

commit_message:
Made service broker to handle asynchronous request

In this commit murano service broker for Cloud Foundry was updated to
handle asynchronous request correctly. So, custom wsgi response
serializer was added to provide correct responses for CF API. Along with
it function for handling continious actions was implemented.

Change-Id: I2c54751f11ec5d5785b5f1e3ba155bc58c7ed0be
Closes-Bug: #1500773
(cherry picked from commit 3c881f813592f767205d5df428f275f718a0f4f2)

commit_message:
Customized response sent in case of fault condition.

When duplicate workbook or workflow is created,
html respose is sent because content type
of result is 'plain/text'.

Code has been change to send 'application/json'
content type in case of exception is araise.

Change-Id: Icef1f8c5c615e21bb9da5a3d3bef9dacd308d242
Closes-Bug: #1501172
(cherry picked from commit 493fcc5f0f9306d58cecd30f6fb3c7b031921b03)

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-13 06:12:10.000000000', 'message': 'Fix argparse error in wsgi script

In mistral/api/wsgi.py script, config.parse_args is called. By default,
oslo.config parses the CLI args if no args is provided. As a result,
invoking the WSGI script from gunicorn leads to the error with argparse
complaining that the CLI options have already been parsed.

Change-Id: Ib04325ae61759f4fc926f107f98a4eae82aec550
Closes-Bug: #1503014
(cherry picked from commit c55a035ffb83283c90914539eefee7dd71abbd40)
'}]
commit_message:
Fix argparse error in wsgi script

In mistral/api/wsgi.py script, config.parse_args is called. By default,
oslo.config parses the CLI args if no args is provided. As a result,
invoking the WSGI script from gunicorn leads to the error with argparse
complaining that the CLI options have already been parsed.

Change-Id: Ib04325ae61759f4fc926f107f98a4eae82aec550
Closes-Bug: #1503014
(cherry picked from commit c55a035ffb83283c90914539eefee7dd71abbd40)

commit_message:
Remove usage of expandtabs() in get_workflow_definition

There's no need to use that function for the purpose of calculating
indentation.

This patch is supplementary to the previouse patch[1], which I have
wrongly pressed workflow+1 button to have it merged. Please see my
comments there.

Fix the wrong indentation of workflow definition as well.

[1]: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/225559/

Change-Id: I8daac2f81989cff83abcb01096bdf84eae5d89eb
(cherry picked from commit e278571b1bf2f2d88087f695d9790cf0c89be3ea)

commit_message:
Add a code-review guideline document

This adds a document that aims to provide a checklist-like review
guideline for code reviewers. We can encode small decisions and tribal
knowledge in this document to help increase consistency.

Right now, this just adds upgrade-related review items as those are
some of the more complicated and least-documented at the moment.

Change-Id: I5bbb7e4e2192b853373fed38ca0ad873fc8b329e

commit_message:
Use wait_for_status instead of wait_for_delete

The enhanced wait_for_status could handle 404 responce and deleted
status to verify deletion of a kind of resource.

Change-Id: I82da4ad782f64176f19b1411dfe9d5cd96b1eafa

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-25 12:42:06.000000000', 'message': 'Build late artifacts without rebuilding fuel packages

Implement flag PATCHING_CI, which is equal 0, means: patching
feature is disabled.

If PATCHING_CI=1, then:

1) Add 7.0-release mirror [1];
2) Build iso with BUILD_PACKAGES=0
   late packages (fuel-bootstrap-image, fuel-target-centos-images,
   fuel-docker-images) should be always build in spite of
   BUILD_PACKAGES flag, since they are depend on the first level
   artifacts (packages);
3) Update requirements-*.txt files with patching approach since
   we need to store original requirements.txt and be sure that
   building staging mirror will produce the same results as for
   release 7.0;
4) Make sure the release version of bootstrap, centos-image and
   docker packages is increasing.
    We need to be sure that packages (in packages-late target):
     - fuel-bootstrap-image
     - fuel-target-centos-images
     - fuel-docker-images
    will increase their release numbers by 1 continuously
    in order to be able to ship them in updates repositories.

[1]. http://mirror.fuel-infra.org/fwm/????/

Change-Id: Ic08af578fc3ce0b5b8bed9cf4d8f0e066ed8c7db

commit_message:
Build late artifacts without rebuilding fuel packages

Implement flag PATCHING_CI, which is equal 0, means: patching
feature is disabled.

If PATCHING_CI=1, then:

1) Add 7.0-release mirror [1]; Can be redefined with
   RELEASE_CENTOS_MIRROR
2) Build iso with BUILD_PACKAGES=0
   late packages (fuel-bootstrap-image, fuel-target-centos-images,
   fuel-docker-images) should be always build in spite of
   BUILD_PACKAGES flag, since they are depend on the first level
   artifacts (packages);
3) Update requirements-*.txt files with patching approach since
   we need to store original requirements.txt and be sure that
   building staging mirror will produce the same results as for
   release 7.0;
4) Make sure the release version of bootstrap, centos-image and
   docker packages is increasing.
    We need to be sure that packages (in packages-late target):
     - fuel-bootstrap-image
     - fuel-target-centos-images
     - fuel-docker-images
    will increase their release numbers by 1 continuously
    in order to be able to ship them in updates repositories.

[1]. http://mirror.fuel-infra.org/fwm/7.0-release

Change-Id: Ic08af578fc3ce0b5b8bed9cf4d8f0e066ed8c7db

Check value format when uploading blob value

Check the value format before uploading a value into store.
If format is incorrect raise appropriare exception.

commit_message:
Stop deployment task based on status in orchestrator

Stop deployment task shold be executed only if tasks
transmitted by orchestrator.

 - stop task manager changed for handling in_orchestrator status
 - in_orchestrator field added to task serializer (required for UI)
 - stop deployment tests fixed for handling in_orchestrator value
 - fake thread for setting in_orchestrator value added

Change-Id: I4e74da54ecd0925c3997acd7530b4b74f6ff844b
Closes-Bug: #1498827

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-31 11:56:39.000000000', 'message': "[WIP] Implementation of keepalived for haproxy

This commit uses a keepalived role, available in
ansible galaxy, to configure keepalived for haproxy
(this may be useful later, if there is a split of
roles from the main repo)

Keepalived makes the haproxy truely HA, by having
haproxy's VIP highly available between the hosts
defined in the inventory.

The keepalived role configuration is fully
documented in the playbooks/role folder.

To configure keepalived on your host, you only have to
give it a variable (dict). A template handles the
generation of the configuration of keepalived.

By default, the variable files defined in vars/configs/
are enough to have a keepalived working for haproxy,
with a master- backup configuration.

The playbook completely relies on the dynamic generation
script to define keepalived hosts. The first host will
be considered as master, the others are slaves.

Change-Id: Ib87a3bb70d6f4b7ac9356e8a28fe4b5936eb9334
"}, {'created': '2015-08-31 14:54:21.000000000', 'message': "[WIP] Implementation of keepalived for haproxy

This commit uses a keepalived role, available in
ansible galaxy, to configure keepalived for haproxy
(this may be useful later, if there is a split of
roles from the main repo)

Keepalived makes the haproxy truely HA, by having
haproxy's VIP highly available between the hosts
defined in the inventory.

The keepalived role configuration is fully
documented in the playbooks/role folder.

To configure keepalived on your host, you only have to
give it a variable (dict). A template handles the
generation of the configuration of keepalived.

By default, the variable files defined in vars/configs/
are enough to have a keepalived working for haproxy,
with a master- backup configuration.

The playbook completely relies on the dynamic generation
script to define keepalived hosts. The first host will
be considered as master, the others are slaves.

The implemented variables are the following:
* keepalived_(ext|int)ernal_vip_cidr
* keepalived_(ext|int)ernal_interface
* keepalived_(ext|int)ernal_virtual_router_id
* keepalived_priority_backup
* keepalived_priority_master

In these variables, only the following variables
are necessary: keepalived_(ext|int)ernal_interface
However, it's recommended to also configure the
keepalived_(ext|int)ernal_interface
(to know which interface the vips can bind on)

Change-Id: Ib87a3bb70d6f4b7ac9356e8a28fe4b5936eb9334

"}, {'created': '2015-09-11 08:34:42.000000000', 'message': "Implementation of keepalived for haproxy

This commit uses a keepalived role, available in
ansible galaxy, to configure keepalived for haproxy

Keepalived makes the haproxy truely HA, by having
haproxy's VIP highly available between the hosts
defined in the inventory.

The keepalived role configuration is fully
documented in the playbooks/role folder.

To configure keepalived on your host, you only have to
give it a variable (dict). A template handles the
generation of the configuration of keepalived.

By default, the variable files defined in vars/configs/
are enough to have a keepalived working for haproxy,
with a master-backup configuration.

The playbook completely relies on the dynamic generation
script to define keepalived hosts. The first host will
be considered as master, the others are slaves.

The implemented variables are the following:
* keepalived_(ext|int)ernal_vip_cidr
* keepalived_(ext|int)ernal_interface
* keepalived_(ext|int)ernal_virtual_router_id
* keepalived_priority_backup
* keepalived_priority_master

In these variables, only the following variables
are necessary: keepalived_(ext|int)ernal_vip_cidr
However, it's recommended to also configure the
keepalived_(ext|int)ernal_interface
(to know which interface the vips can bind on)

Closes-Bug: 1414397
Change-Id: Ib87a3bb70d6f4b7ac9356e8a28fe4b5936eb9334

'}, {'created': '2015-09-30 12:43:45.000000000', 'message': '[WIP] Implementation of keepalived for haproxy

This commit uses a keepalived role, available in
ansible galaxy, to configure keepalived for haproxy

Keepalived makes the haproxy truely HA, by having
haproxy's VIP highly available between the hosts
defined in the inventory.

The keepalived role configuration is fully
documented on the upstream role.

To configure keepalived on your host, you only have to
give it a variable (dict). A template handles the
generation of the configuration of keepalived.

By default, the variable files defined in vars/configs/
are enough to have a keepalived working for haproxy,
with a master-backup configuration.

You can define other variable files by setting
haproxy_keepalived_(master|backup)_vars in your
user_variables. This should point to a "variable
template" file like the one you can find
in vars/configs/*

The haproxy playbook has been changed to rely on
the dynamic generation script. It will use the env.d
to have haproxy hosts. The first host from the
generated inventory will be considered as master,
while the others are slaves. The keepalived role
will only run if more than haproxy host is found
in the inventory. This behaviour can be changed
and keepalived can be disabled by the variable:
haproxy_use_keepalived.

The implemented variables are the following:
* haproxy_keepalived_(ext|int)ernal_vip_cidr
* haproxy_keepalived_(ext|int)ernal_interface
* haproxy_keepalived_(ext|int)ernal_virtual_router_id
* haproxy_keepalived_priority_backup
* haproxy_keepalived_priority_master
* haproxy_keepalived_master_vars
* haproxy_keepalived_backup_vars

In these variables, only the following variables
are necessary: keepalived_(ext|int)ernal_vip_cidr
However, it's recommended to also configure the
keepalived_(ext|int)ernal_interface
(to know which interface the vips can bind on)

Closes-Bug: 1414397

commit_message:
Implementation of keepalived for haproxy

This commit uses a keepalived role, available in
ansible galaxy, to configure keepalived for haproxy

Keepalived makes the haproxy truely HA, by having
haproxy's VIP highly available between the hosts
defined in the inventory.

The keepalived role configuration is fully
documented on the upstream role.

To configure keepalived on your host, you only have to
give it a variable (dict). A template handles the
generation of the configuration of keepalived.

By default, the variable files defined in vars/configs/
are enough to have a keepalived working for haproxy,
with a master-backup configuration.

You can define other variable files by setting
haproxy_keepalived_(master|backup)_vars in your
user_variables. This should point to a "variable
template" file like the one you can find
in vars/configs/*

The haproxy playbook has been changed to rely on
the dynamic generation script. It will use the env.d
to have haproxy hosts. The first host from the
generated inventory will be considered as master,
while the others are slaves. The keepalived role
will only run if more than haproxy host is found
in the inventory. This behaviour can be changed
and keepalived can be disabled by the variable:
haproxy_use_keepalived.

The implemented variables are the following:
* haproxy_keepalived_(ext|int)ernal_vip_cidr
* haproxy_keepalived_(ext|int)ernal_interface
* haproxy_keepalived_(ext|int)ernal_virtual_router_id
* haproxy_keepalived_priority_backup
* haproxy_keepalived_priority_master
* haproxy_keepalived_vars_file

In these variables, only the following variables
are necessary: keepalived_(ext|int)ernal_vip_cidr
However, it's recommended to also configure the
keepalived_(ext|int)ernal_interface
(to know which interface the vips can bind on)

Closes-Bug: 1414397
Change-Id: Ib87a3bb70d6f4b7ac9356e8a28fe4b5936eb9334
